<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Walter Benjamin</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Tue Jan 18, 2011; substantive revision Tue Dec 23, 2025</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
Walter Benjamin&rsquo;s importance as a philosopher and critical
theorist can be gauged by the diversity of his intellectual influence
and the continuing productivity of his thought. Primarily regarded as
a literary critic and essayist, the philosophical basis of
Benjamin&rsquo;s writings has, over the last 50 years, been
increasingly acknowledged. These writings were a decisive influence
upon Theodor W. Adorno&rsquo;s conception of philosophy&rsquo;s
actuality or adequacy to the present (Adorno 1931) and on
&ldquo;Frankfurt School&rdquo; Critical Theory&rsquo;s broader attempt
to develop a politically oriented, materialist aesthetic theory.</p>

<p>
The delayed appearance of Benjamin&rsquo;s collected writings has
determined and sustained the Anglophone reception of his work. A
limited-edition hectograph (&lsquo;In Memory of Walter
Benjamin&rsquo;), which contained his theses &lsquo;On the Concept of
History&rsquo;, was first published &ndash; two years after
Benjamin&rsquo;s death &ndash; by the Institute for Social Research in
1942, but a two-volume selection of his writings was only published in
German in 1955, with a full edition not appearing until
1972&ndash;1989, and a 21-volume critical edition, in production since
2008, scheduled to be completed in 2027; English anthologies first
appeared in 1968 and 1978, and the four-volume Selected Writings
between 1996 and 2003.</p>

<p>
These delays were in part the result of disputes &ndash; primarily
between Hannah Arendt, and Theodor Adorno and Gershom Scholem &ndash;
over the ownership of Benjamin&rsquo;s literary estate and legacy,
controversies that resurfaced in the late 1960s and again in the early
2020s, and which continue to shape his reception and interpretation.
The two-volume collection of Benjamin&rsquo;s <em>Schriften</em>
(edited by Adorno and published in 1955) included examples of his
philosophical, historical and city writings. The subsequent selection
of essays for the first (shorter) English collection,
<em>Illuminations</em> (edited by Arendt in 1968), prioritized
Benjamin&rsquo;s literary criticism (with the exception of the theses
&lsquo;On the Concept of History&rsquo;), reflecting Arendt&rsquo;s
presentation of him, in her introduction to the collection, as a
&ldquo;metaphorical&rdquo; or &ldquo;poetical&rdquo; thinker, who like
a &ldquo;pearl diver&rdquo; sought to bring back &ldquo;thought
fragments&rdquo; from the depths of the past (Arendt 1968,
41&ndash;2).</p>

<p>
This contested reception of Benjamin&rsquo;s works partly reflected
and partly produced a sense of Benjamin&rsquo;s thought as
inconsistent, thereby establishing the task of academic scholarship
after his death: on the one hand, &ldquo;any attempt to establish a
unity from a series of texts as clearly diverse as Benjamin&rsquo;s
will always be thwarted&rdquo; (Benjamin, A. 1986, 30) so that
&ldquo;even his best readers sometime treat his corpus of writing as a
vast array of brilliant and idiosyncratic insights with hardly more to
unify them than the sense that they all bear the stamp of
Benjamin&rsquo;s unique and unclassifiable genius&rdquo; (Friedlander
2012, 2); on the other hand, Scholem and Adorno sought for an
underlying coherence to Benjamin&rsquo;s thought, either in Jewish
mysticism or European philosophy, that continues to animate some of
the most important interpretations of his work. Kohlenbach (2002,
x-xi), for example, has argued that &ldquo;in contrast to (secular)
theory and philosophy&rdquo; it is &ldquo;Benjamin&rsquo;s
religiosity&rdquo; that is essential not only to his direct engagement
with religious ideas but also &ldquo;to both the apparently academic
and the most &lsquo;materialist&rsquo; parts of Benjamin&rsquo;s
work&rdquo;, whereas Friedlander (2012, 2) has argued for &ldquo;the
philosophical armature that &hellip;holds his writings together&rsquo;
and &lsquo;gather[s]&hellip; into a unity of thinking the disparate
moments of Benjamin&rsquo;s writings&rdquo;. One way to reconcile
these claims is to understand Benjamin&rsquo;s approach as a
&ldquo;philosophizing beyond philosophy&rdquo; (Caygill 1998, 120),
which, driven by a transdisciplinary and historical impulse (Osborne
2011), draws upon ostensibly non-philosophical thought in order to
complete its philosophical task.</p>

<p>
Originally received in the context of literary theory and aesthetics,
only in the last decades of the 20th century did the philosophical
depth and cultural breadth of Benjamin&rsquo;s thought begin to be
fully appreciated. Despite the voluminous size of the secondary
literature that it has produced, his work remains a continuing source
of productivity. An understanding of the intellectual context of his
work has contributed to the philosophical revival of Early German
Romanticism. His philosophy of language has played a seminal role in
translation theory. His essay on &lsquo;The Work of Art in the Age of
Its Technological Reproducibility&rsquo; remains a major theoretical
text for film theory. <em>One-Way Street</em> and the work arising
from his unfinished research on nineteenth century Paris (<em>The
Arcades Project</em>), provide a theoretical stimulus for cultural
theory and philosophical concepts of the modern. Benjamin&rsquo;s
messianic understanding of history has been an enduring source of
theoretical fascination and frustration for a diverse range of
philosophical thinkers, including Jacques Derrida, Giorgio Agamben
and, in a critical context, J&uuml;rgen Habermas. The &lsquo;Critique
of Violence&rsquo; and &lsquo;On the Concept of History&rsquo; are
important sources for Derrida&rsquo;s discussion of messianicity,
which has been influential, along with Paul de Man&rsquo;s discussion
of allegory, for the poststructuralist reception of Benjamin&rsquo;s
writings. Aspects of Benjamin&rsquo;s thought have also been
associated with a revival of political theology, although it is
doubtful this reception is true to the tendencies of Benjamin&rsquo;s
own political thought. More recently, interest in Benjamin&rsquo;s
philosophy of education has been fuelled by the translations of his
<em>Early Writings</em> in 2011 and the transcripts of his radio
broadcasts for children (<em>Radio Benjamin</em>) in 2014.</p>
</div> 

