<hr /></div>

<div id="main-text">

<h2><a id="BioSke">1. Biographical Sketch</a></h2>

<p>
Walter Bendix Schoenflies Benjamin was born on July 15, 1892, the
eldest of three children in a prosperous Berlin family from an
assimilated Jewish background. At the age of 13, after a prolonged
period of sickness, Benjamin was sent to a progressive co-educational
boarding school in Haubinda, Thuringia, where he formed an important
intellectual kinship with the liberal educational reformer Gustav
Wyneken. On his return to Berlin, he began contributing to <em>Der
Anfang</em> (&lsquo;The Beginning&rsquo;), a journal dedicated to
Wyneken&rsquo;s principles on the spiritual purity of youth, articles
which contain in embryonic form important ideas on experience and
history that continue to occupy his mature thought. As a student at
the universities of Freiburg im Breisgau and Berlin, Benjamin attended
lectures by the neo-Kantian philosopher Heinrich Rickert and the
sociologist Georg Simmel, whilst continuing to be actively involved in
the growing Youth Movement. In 1914, however, Benjamin denounced his
mentor and withdrew from the movement in response to a public lecture
in which Wyneken praised the ethical experience that the outbreak of
war afforded the young. In 1915 a friendship began between Benjamin
and Gerhard (later Gershom) Scholem, a fellow student at Berlin. This
relationship would have a lifelong influence upon Benjamin&rsquo;s
relation to Judaism and Kabbalism, notably in his interpretations of
Kafka in the early 1930s and in the messianic interpretation of the
Paul Klee painting <em>Angelus Novus</em> in his later theses
&lsquo;On the Concept of History&rsquo;. Scholem would prove
instrumental in establishing and, in part, shaping the legacy of
Benjamin&rsquo;s works after his death (Raz-Krakotzkin 2013).</p>

<p>
Benjamin&rsquo;s doctoral dissertation, &lsquo;The Concept of Art
Criticism in German Romanticism&rsquo;, was awarded, <em>summa cum
laude</em>, by the University of Bern, Switzerland, in 1919. His
celebrated essay on Goethe&rsquo;s novella, <em>The Elective
Affinities</em>, was begun shortly after and put into practice the
theory of art criticism developed in his dissertation.
Benjamin&rsquo;s <em>Habilitationsschrift</em> on the <em>Origin of
the German Mourning-Play</em> (<em>Ursprung des deutschen
Trauerspiels</em>)&mdash;the thesis which would have enabled him to
become a professional academic&mdash;had, he feared, with the death of
his intellectual ally, the Protestant theologian Florens Christian
Rang, lost its &ldquo;proper reader&rdquo; (GB 3:16). In 1925, he was
forced to withdraw his submission from the University of Frankfurt am
Main and with it the possibility of a future academic position.
However, despite this academic failure, an excerpt from the work
appeared in a literary journal two years later and the book was
published the following year (1928), quickly receiving favourable
attention in a number of well-regarded newspapers and periodicals in
Germany and further afield (Brodersen 1996, 154). In an ironic twist,
Benjamin&rsquo;s failed <em>Habilitation</em> study became the subject
of a seminar course taught at Frankfurt University in 1932&ndash;3 by
Theodor Wiesengrund (later Theodor W. Adorno).</p>

<p>
Much of the writing for his thesis was completed in 1924 on the
Italian island of Capri, where Benjamin had retreated for financial
reasons. The stay would prove decisive, however, since it was here he
met the Bolshevik Latvian theatre producer Asja Lacis, with whom he
begun an erotically frustrated but intellectually productive
relationship. &lsquo;Naples&rsquo; was jointly written with Lacis in
1925, whilst <em>One-Way Street</em>, a quasi-constructivist
collection of fragments written between 1923&ndash;1926 and dedicated
to Lacis on its publication in 1928, and the unfinished <em>Arcades
Project</em>, begun in the late 1920s, both exhibit a modernist
experimentation with form that can in part be attributed to
Lacis&rsquo; influence. His Marxist turn towards historical
materialism was compounded by his enthusiastic study of Georg
Luk&aacute;cs&rsquo; <em>History and Class Consciousness</em> whilst
on Capri and a visit to Lacis in Soviet Moscow in the winter of
1926&ndash;7.</p>

<p>
By the early 1930s Benjamin was closely involved in the plans for a
left-wing periodical to be entitled &lsquo;Crisis and Critique&rsquo;,
in collaboration with Ernst Bloch, Sigfried Kracauer and, among
others, the Marxist poet, playwright and theatre director Bertolt
Brecht (Wizisla 2009, 66&ndash;98). Benjamin had been introduced to
Brecht by Lacis in 1929 and over the following decade developed a
close personal friendship, in which their literary and political
affinities had been cemented under the difficult conditions of
political exile. Benjamin undertook a series of studies of
Brecht&rsquo;s &ldquo;epic theatre&rdquo; and modelled the radio
broadcasts he wrote and presented during this period upon the
latter&rsquo;s experiments in theatrical didacticism (Brodersen 1996,
193). In 1933, Benjamin departed Nazi Germany for the last time,
following Adorno, Brecht and many other Jewish friends into an exile
he divided between Paris, Ibiza, San Remo and Brecht&rsquo;s house
near Svendborg, Denmark.</p>

<p>
During the 1930s the Institute for Social Research, by this point
under the directorship of Horkheimer and exiled from its base in the
University of Frankfurt, provided Benjamin with important
opportunities for publishing as well as an increasingly necessary
financial stipend, his primary source of income. Theodor W. Adorno,
who had been introduced to Benjamin a decade earlier by a mutual
friend, Siegfried Kracauer, was instrumental in securing this support.
An important consequence of this dependence, however, was the
editorial revisions to which key essays in which Benjamin developed
his materialist theory of art were subjected, such as &lsquo;The Work
of Art in the Age of Its Technical Reproducibility&rsquo; and those on
Baudelaire and Paris that grew out of <em>The Arcades Project</em>.
Arendt had claimed that, in particular, Benjamin&rsquo;s friendship
with Brecht &lsquo;endangered his relation to the Institute of Social
Research,&rsquo; leading to a fear the Institute would withdraw its
financial support and Benjamin&rsquo;s consequent docility towards
their editorial suggestions (Arendt 1968). Recent scholarship
(Erazo-Heufelder 2017; Mulder 2015; Fleck 2023) has offered a more
critical view of the Institute&rsquo;s mismanagement of funds and
inequitable distribution of financial and administrative support,
partially corroborating Arendt&rsquo;s concerns.</p>

<p>
With the outbreak of war in 1939, Benjamin was temporarily interned in
the French &ldquo;concentration camps&rdquo; established for German
citizens. On his release a few months later he returned to Paris and
there continued his work in the Biblioth&egrave;que Nationale on
<em>The Arcades Project</em>. The notes for his unfinished research
were left in the safekeeping of librarian and friend, the writer
Georges Bataille, as Benjamin fled Paris before the advancing German
army in the summer of 1940. The last few months of Benjamin&rsquo;s
life reflect the precarious experience of countless other Jewish
Germans in Vichy France: a flight to the border and preparations for
emigration. Lacking the necessary exit visa from France, he joined a
guided party that crossed the Pyrenees in an attempt to enter Spain as
illegal refugees. Turned back by customs officials, Benjamin took his
life in the small, Spanish border town of Port Bou, on September 27,
1940.</p>

<h2><a id="EarWorKanExp">2. Early Works: Kant and Experience</a></h2>

<p>
The importance of Benjamin&rsquo;s early unpublished fragments for an
understanding his wider philosophical project has been emphasised by a
number of scholars (Wolfharth 1992; Caygill 1998; Rrenban 2005).
Indeed, without them it becomes difficult to understand the
intellectual context and historical tradition out of which Benjamin is
writing and therefore nearly impossible to grasp the philosophical
underpinnings of his works. Of Benjamin&rsquo;s earliest published
writing his attempt in the essay entitled &lsquo;Experience&rsquo;
(&lsquo;<em>Erfahrung</em>&rsquo;, 1913/1914) to distinguish an
alternative and superior concept of experience provides a useful
introduction to a central and enduring preoccupation of his thought.
Benjamin&rsquo;s concern with delineating an immediate and
metaphysical experience of spirit is valuable in providing a thematic
description of a conceptual opposition working throughout his thought.
Filtered here through the cultural ideals of the Youth Movement, this
contrasts the empty, spiritless [<em>Geistlosen</em>] and unartistic
&ldquo;experiences&rdquo; accumulated over a life merely lived-through
[<em>erlebt</em>] with that privileged kind of experience which is
filled with spiritual content through its enduring contact with the
dreams of youth (SW 1, 3&ndash;6). The influence of Nietzsche in these
earlier texts is discernible (McFarland 2013), particularly, in the
importance the young Benjamin places upon aesthetic experience in
overcoming the embittered nihilism of contemporary values (although he
is unable to articulate this cultural transformation here beyond a
vague appeal to the canon of German poets: Schiller, Goethe,
H&ouml;lderlin, and Stefan George).</p>

<p>
By 1918 the attempt at a more systematic and philosophically
sophisticated understanding of a &ldquo;higher concept of
experience&rdquo; (SW 1, 102) within what Benjamin now calls
&ldquo;the coming philosophy&rdquo; is articulated in relation to
Kant&rsquo;s transcendental idealism. Benjamin argues that the value
of Platonic and Kantian philosophy lies in its attempt to secure the
scope and depth of knowledge through justification, exemplified in the
way Kant conducts a critical inquiry into the transcendental
conditions of knowledge. But this Kantian attempt to grasp a certain
and timeless knowledge is in turn based upon an empirical concept of
experience which is restricted, Benjamin argues, to that &ldquo;naked,
primitive, self evident&rdquo; experience of the Enlightenment, whose
paradigm is Newtonian physics (SW 1, 101). Despite Kant&rsquo;s
introduction of a transcendental subject, his system remains tied to a
na&iuml;ve empiricist understanding of experience, of the kind
privileged in the positivist scientific tradition as the encounter
between a distinct subject (conceived as a cognizing consciousness
receiving sensible intuitions) and object (understood as a
sensation-causing thing-in-itself).</p>

<p>
In contrast, the pre-Enlightenment concept of experience invested the
world with a deeper and more profound significance, because the
Creation assumes a revelatory religious importance. This is apparent
not only in the deeply Christian world-view of mediaeval Europe but
survives in secularized form in Renaissance and Baroque humanism, and
in &ldquo;Counter-Enlightenment&rdquo; thinkers such as J. G. Hamann,
Goethe, and the Romantics. Benjamin suggests that the &ldquo;great
transformation and correction which must be performed upon the concept
of experience, oriented so one-sidedly along mathematical-mechanical
lines, can be attained only by relating knowledge to language, as was
attempted by Hamann during Kant&rsquo;s lifetime&rdquo; (SW 1,
107&ndash;8). In the essay &lsquo;On Language as Such and the Language
of Man&rsquo; (&lsquo;<em>&Uuml;ber Sprache &uuml;berhaupt und
&uuml;ber die Sprache des Menschen</em>&rsquo;, c. 1916), Benjamin
offers a theological conception of language which draws on
Hamann&rsquo;s discussion of Creation as the physical imprint of the
divine Word of God, to claim that there &ldquo;is no event or thing in
either animate or inanimate nature that does not in some way partake
of language&rdquo; (SW 1, 62&ndash;3). This implies that all
experience&mdash;including perception&mdash;is essentially linguistic,
whilst all human language (including writing, typically associated
with mere convention) is inherently expressive and creative. Language
is privileged as a model of experience in these early essays precisely
because it undermines and transgresses the neat divisions and
limitations operating in the Kantian system, including that
fundamental one that distinguishes between the subject and object of
sensations. If both are constitutively linguistic, language serves as
a medium of experience that binds the ostensible &ldquo;subject&rdquo;
and &ldquo;object&rdquo; in a more profound, perhaps mystical,
relationship of underlying kinship. More generally, Hamann&rsquo;s
metacritique provides Benjamin with a sense of the hypocrisy of the
Kantian separation of understanding and sensibility on the basis of an
empty and purely formal notion of pure reason, which can itself only
be postulated according to the concrete, aesthetic content of
language.</p>

<p>
Whilst Benjamin is not interested in returning to the pre-critical
project of a rationalist deduction of experience, nor to a directly
religious conception of the world, he is interested in how the
scientific concept of experience that Kant is utilising distorts the
structure of Kant&rsquo;s philosophical system, and how this might be
corrected with the use of theological concepts. Epistemology must
address not only &ldquo;the question of the certainty of knowledge
that is lasting&rdquo;, but also the neglected question of &ldquo;the
integrity of an experience that is ephemeral&rdquo; (SW 1, 100).
Benjamin&rsquo;s suggestion as to how this project might be formulated
within the Kantian system is sketchy, but nonetheless indicates some
of the preoccupying concerns of his later writings. In general, it
involves the expansion of the limited spatio-temporal forms and
essentially causal-mechanistic categories of Kant&rsquo;s philosophy
through the integration of, for example, religious, historical,
artistic, linguistic and psychological experiences. Benjamin&rsquo;s
enduring concern with the new, the outmoded and the heteronomous
reflect this attempt to integrate more speculative phenomenological
possibilities of experience into the remit of philosophical knowledge.
It resists privileging any single discipline of knowledge, preserving
a multiplicity that implicates truth in the problem of aesthetic
representation. This would lead Benjamin to attempt a radical
rethinking of the philosophical concept of the Idea, away from its
dualistic associations with a timeless and purely rational essence of
things.</p>

<p>
Benjamin also believes that a more speculative metaphysics would
necessitate the abolishment of the sharp distinction between Nature
and Freedom&mdash;or causal mechanism and moral willing&mdash;in
Kant&rsquo;s architectonic. Since it is a specific understanding of
&ldquo;dialectic&rdquo; which mediates between these two spheres in
Kant&rsquo;s critical system, this entails a speculative rethinking of
the Kantian dialectic. This suggests that new possibilities of
syllogistic logical relations might themselves be opened up, including
what he calls &ldquo;a certain nonsynthesis of two concepts in
another&rdquo; (SW 1, 106; cf. Weber 2008, 48). The relation of
nonsynthesis hinted at here can be seen to inform Benjamin&rsquo;s
understanding of the Idea as a constellation of extremes in the
<em>Origin of the German Mourning-Play</em> and of the dialectical
image in his mature writings. In this sense, Benjamin&rsquo;s
metacritique of Kant represents an attempt to construct an alternative
post-Kantian tradition to that of Hegelian dialectics. It therefore
required a new philosophy of history.</p>

<h2><a id="RomGoeCri">3. Romanticism, Goethe and Criticism</a></h2>

<p>
Benjamin initially sought to develop these ideas in the context of
Kant&rsquo;s philosophy of history, believing it was in this context
that the problems of the Kantian system could be fully exposed and
challenged (C, 98). A very early article, &lsquo;The Life of
Students&rsquo; (&lsquo;<em>Das Leben der Studenten</em>&rsquo;,
1915), is useful for suggesting how these problems manifest themselves
within the philosophy of history. It rejects a &ldquo;a view of
history that puts its faith in the infinite extent of time and thus
concerns itself only with the speed, or lack of it, with which people
and epochs advance along the path of progress&rdquo; and contrasts
this with a perspective &ldquo;in which history appears to be
concentrated on a single focal point, like those that had
traditionally been found in the utopian images of the
philosophers&rdquo; (SW 1, 37). The latter, &lsquo;messianic&rsquo;
view of history has a distinct intention and methodology: it aims to
grasp how elements of what Benjamin calls &ldquo;the ultimate
condition&rdquo; and &ldquo;highest metaphysical state&rdquo; of
history&mdash;which we might call the historical Absolute&mdash;appear
not as the <em>telos</em> or end of history, but as an immanent state
of perfection which has the potential to manifest itself in any
particular moment (SW 1, 37). He claims that the necessary recognition
of such metaphysical condition requires an act of criticism
[<em>Kritik</em>] (SW 1, 38). Benjamin had initially proposed
Kant&rsquo;s philosophy of history as the topic of his doctoral
dissertation, and while he felt it necessary to change this to the
Early German Romantics&rsquo; philosophy of art, crucial features of
the proposed project survive in the final work. Astute readers, he
says, may still discern in it an &ldquo;insight into the relationship
of a truth to history&rdquo; (C, 135&ndash;6). Specifically, the
concept of art criticism operating in Romantic aesthetics rests upon
epistemological presuppositions that reveal the
&lsquo;messianic&rsquo; essence of Romanticism (SW 1, 116&ndash;7;
n.3, 185). The messianic conjunction between the highest metaphysical
state of history and the ephemerality of each particular moment is
here seen as theoretically determining the Romantic relationship
between the artistic Absolute&mdash;or what Benjamin defines as the
Idea of art&mdash;and each particular artwork.</p>

<p>
In his doctoral dissertation, Benjamin argues that the philosophical
relationship between the Idea of art and particular artworks posited
in Romantic aesthetics must be understood in relation to
Fichte&rsquo;s theory of reflection. This sought to ground the
possibility of a certain and immediate type of cognition without
recourse to the problematic notion of an intellectual intuition. For
Fichte, reflection indicates the free activity of consciousness taking
itself as its own object of thought: its capacity for thinking of
thinking. In doing so, the initial form of thinking is transformed
into its content. In such reflection, thought seems capable of
immediately grasping itself as a thinking subject and therefore of
possessing a certain kind of immediate and foundational knowledge.
Although Benjamin introduces a number of specific criticisms of
Fichte&rsquo;s philosophical position in his dissertation, he
nonetheless values the Fichtean concept of reflection for providing
the epistemological foundation of Friedrich Schlegel&rsquo;s and
Novalis&rsquo; understandings of the metaphysical function of art
criticism. Some scholars have, however, questioned the accuracy of
Benjamin&rsquo;s interpretation of Fichte&rsquo;s concept of
reflection and the importance he accords to it in Romantic
epistemology (Bullock 1987, 78&ndash;93; Menninghaus 2005,
29&ndash;44).</p>

<p>
Unlike in Fichte, here immediacy and infinitude are not mutually
exclusive aspects of cognition. The uniqueness of the Romantic concept
of the Absolute resides in the fact that the Romantic conception of
infinitude regards it not as empty but &ldquo;substantial and
filled&rdquo; (SW 1, 129). Benjamin argued that the Romantics
specifically identified this structure of the Absolute with the Idea
of art, and in particular with artistic form (SW 1, 135). Art
criticism becomes central to this concept of infinite fulfilment
because, like the epistemological relation between reflection and
thought in Fichte, criticism both consummates the finite and
particular work by raising it to a higher level&mdash;in which the
form of the work is transformed into content as the object of
criticism&mdash;and simultaneously connects the work&rsquo;s
particular artistic form with the continuity and unity of absolute
form in the Idea of art. Criticism is, for the Romantics, the
continuation and ongoing completion of the particular work through its
infinite connection with other art works and works of criticism. By
conceiving the Idea of art as a &lsquo;medium of reflection&rsquo;,
the early Romantics dissolve the Enlightenment world-view of the
positive sciences that Fichte inherited from Kant, and in doing so
overcome the critical injunctions placed upon the experience of the
infinite (SW 1, 132; 131). This conception of a fulfilled infinity
constitutes the messianism that Benjamin claims is essential to Early
Romantic epistemology.</p>

<p>
In the version of the dissertation formally submitted to the
university, Benjamin concludes by identifying the Romantic theory of
art criticism with &lsquo;the consummation of the work&rsquo; (SW 1,
177). The artwork provides the immanent criterion for critical
reflection, which in turn completes the work by raising it into an
autonomous and higher existence. This immanent criticism rejects both
the dogmatic imposition of external rules (such as those of classical
aesthetics) and the dissolution of aesthetic criteria (with the appeal
to artistic genius). It provides, Benjamin thought, one of the
fundamental legacies for a modern concept of art criticism. The
version circulated amongst friends and colleagues does not conclude
with a complete affirmation of Romanticism, however, but contains a
critical afterword that renders explicit the critical objections that
Benjamin had carefully inserted into the text. These suggest that the
Romantic theory of art, and by implication the structure of the
Absolute it is grounded upon, is problematically one-sided and
incomplete with regard to (1) its formalism, (2) its positivity, and
(3) its singularity.</p>

<ol>

<li>

<p>
Since the content of each, successive, level of reflection is supplied
by the form of its object, the criticism unfolds the germ of immanent
criticizability contained in each particular artwork&rsquo;s form.
This formalism precludes any serious discussion of the artwork&rsquo;s
specific content.</p></li>

<li>

<p>
Conversely, anything immanently uncriticizable cannot constitute a
true work of art. As a consequence, Romantic criticism is unable to
differentiate between good or bad artworks, since its only criterion
is whether a work <em>is</em> or <em>is not</em> art. Such criticism
is entirely positive in its evaluation, and lacks the important
negative moment essential to judgement.</p></li>

<li>

<p>
Finally, Schlegel &ldquo;committed the old error of confounding
&lsquo;abstract and &lsquo;universal&rsquo; when he believed he had to
make that [Absolute] ground [of art] into an individual&rdquo;,
Benjamin claims (SW 1, 166&ndash;7). He therefore gave a &ldquo;false
interpretation&rdquo; of the unity of all works when he conceived this
as pertaining to some mystical, singular and transcendental
work.</p></li>
</ol>

<p>
The consequent need for what Benjamin presents as a Goethean
modification of Early German Romanticism is laid out in the afterword.
The relation between these criticisms of Romanticism and
Goethe&rsquo;s thought is suggested in the claim that,
&ldquo;Ultimately the mystical thesis that art itself is one
work&hellip;stands in exact correlation with the principle which
asserts the indestructibility of works that are purified in
irony&rdquo; (SW 1, 167). With its mistaken emphasis on the
singularity of the Idea of art, Romantic fulfilment only coincides
with the infinity of the unconditioned, meaning that fulfilment is an
essentially non-historical category of the infinite. Such criticism
cannot be described as judgement, since all authentic judgement
involves an essential negative moment of completion in
&ldquo;self-annihilation&rdquo; (SW 1, 152). Consequently, because
&lsquo;Romantic messianism is not at work in its full force&rsquo;
here (SW 1, 168), the Romantics were increasingly forced to turn to
the &ldquo;accoutrements&rdquo; of ethics, religion and politics to
provide the content required to complete their theory of art.</p>

<p>
Goethe&rsquo;s conception of aesthetic judgement and his principle of
the &lsquo;uncriticizability&rsquo; of great works provided Benjamin
with a way of thinking the necessary modification to the Early German
Romantic Idea of art. His explication of the implicit metaphysical
structure of Goethe&rsquo;s corresponding Ideal of art reveals the
contrasting features of his structure of the Absolute: as a sphere of
pure content, a medium of destructive <em>refraction</em>, and a
plurality of discontinuous archetypes (Charles 2020, 53&ndash;67).
Because finite, particular works can never be romanticized into the
unity of an individual Absolute, they remains immanently incomplete
and yet nonetheless incapable of higher consummation: a
&ldquo;torso&rdquo;, dismembered in relation to the whole, corpse-like
in its deadness. In this context, the true task of criticism becomes
not the consummation of the living work, but that destructive
completion of the dying one.</p>

<p>
Benjamin&rsquo;s essay on &lsquo;Goethe&rsquo;s <em>Elective
Affinities</em>&rsquo; (1924&ndash;5) provides an exemplary piece of
such criticism, whilst developing the concept further by situating it
more explicitly within the context of history. Here, criticism is
charged with the task of revealing what Benjamin calls the
&ldquo;truth content of a work of art&rdquo;, which is intimately
bound up with its &ldquo;material content&rdquo; at the beginning of
the work&rsquo;s history (SW 1, 297). In contrast to mere
commentary&mdash;which proceeds no further than a consideration of
these now historically anachronistic features of its material
content&mdash;the aim of criticism is the destruction of this outer
layer in order for the work&rsquo;s inner truth content to be grasped.
The fundamental philological error of commentary is merely to situate
the work in relation to the &ldquo;lived experience
[<em>Erlebnis</em>]&rdquo; of its author&rsquo;s biographical life
(exemplified in Friedrich Gundolf&rsquo;s 1916 biography of
<em>Goethe</em>), instead of the broader medium of historical
reception through which it has passed down to the contemporary critic.
Benjamin&rsquo;s Romantic theory of immanent criticism insists that
the work must contain its own inner criterion, such that the critic
proceeds from the work itself and not from the life of the author (SW
1, 321). Beginning, therefore, with the odd and striking features of
Goethe&rsquo;s work that come to preoccupy later critics, Benjamin
examines how these are derived from techniques borrowed from the
distinct form of the novella. This novella-like construction grants
the <em>Elective Affinities</em> its strange, fable-like quality,
which differentiates it from the naturalism of a typical novel. It is
this mythical layer, as the real material content of the work, which
expresses the presence of a pantheistic and &ldquo;daemonic&rdquo;
attitude toward nature in Goethe&rsquo;s work.</p>

<p>
Truth content, in contrast, is not to be sought in the conspicuous
features of the work&rsquo;s technique, but in the unity of its
distinct form. The task of criticism is to make this truth content an
object of experience. It concerns itself not with the life or
intentions of the artist, but with that semblance or appearance of
life that the work itself possesses by virtue of its mimetic capacity
for representation: its linguistic expressiveness, which is described
as a verging and bordering on life (SW 1, 350). What is essential to
art, however, and what distinguishes it from the semblance of nature,
is the &ldquo;expressionless [<em>Ausdruckslose</em>]&rdquo;: that
critical violence within the work of art that &ldquo;arrests this
semblance, spellbinds the movement, and interrupts the harmony&rdquo;
(SW 1, 340). &ldquo;Only the expressionless completes the work&rdquo;
<em>as</em> a work of art, Benjamin argues, and it does so by
shattering the work&rsquo;s semblance of unity, the false appearance
of totality pertaining to it. Unlike the intensification of Romantic
reflection, when this semblance itself becomes the object of a
higher-level semblance, a refractive dissonance is opened up. Drawing
on H&ouml;lderlin&rsquo;s concept of the caesura to describe this
moment, Benjamin calls it a &ldquo;counter-rhythmic rupture&rdquo; (SW
1, 341). In focusing its efforts on representing this caesura, genuine
criticism in turn deepens the refractive violence, performing a
destructive or mortuary act of self-annihilation upon the work.</p>

<p>
Art, at the very limit of its mimetic capacity, draws attention to its
construction and in doing so finds the resources to encapsulate a
deeper truth. It is against what Benjamin calls the Christian-mystical
certainty in future reconciliation (which Goethe inserts into the
conclusion of the novella as an attempt to counter the mythical
fatalism which holds sway elsewhere) that he instead endorses the
paradoxical glimmer of hope identified with the image of a shooting
star which appears in Goethe&rsquo;s novella (SW 1, 354&ndash;5). If
the image of the star retains its relationship to the symbolic here,
it does so in accordance with Benjamin&rsquo;s earlier description of
the expressionless as &ldquo;the torso of a symbol&rdquo; (SW 1, 340).
However, it might be better to understand the significance of the
caesura here in the context of the theory of allegory. This is only
properly formulated in Benjamin&rsquo;s next major work, his thesis on
the <em>Origin of the German Mourning-Play</em> (<em>Ursprung des
deutschen Trauerspiels</em>, 1928).</p>

<h2><a id="BarCon">4. Baroque Constellations</a></h2>

<p>
&lsquo;Mourning-play&rsquo; (<em>Trauerspiel</em>) is a term used to
characterise a type of drama that emerges during the baroque period of
art history in the late 16th and early 17th century. The principle
examples discussed in Benjamin&rsquo;s thesis come not from its great
exponents, Pedro Calder&oacute;n de la Barca and William Shakespeare,
but the German dramatists Martin Opitz, Andreas Gryphius, Johann
Christian Hallmann, Daniel Caspar von Lohenstein, and August Adolf von
Haugwitz. Their plays are characterised by a simplicity of action
which is comparable to the classicism of earlier Renaissance theatre,
but also contain peculiarly baroque features. These include an
exaggerated and violent bombast in their language (including a
figurative tendency towards linguistic contraction), an absence of
psychological depth in its characters, a preponderance of and
dependency upon theatrical props and machinery, and a crude emphasis
on violence, suffering and death (cf. Newman 2011; Ferber 2013).</p>

<p>
Leaving aside for now the methodological introduction (referred to in
English as the &lsquo;Epistemo-Critical Prologue&rsquo;), the first
part of Benjamin&rsquo;s thesis is concerned with repudiating the
dogmatic attempt by later critics to impose onto these plays the
external criteria of Aristotelian aesthetics, which are rooted in
classical tragedy. Benjamin&rsquo;s understanding of tragedy here (and
his approach to the mourning-play in general) is partially influenced
by Friedrich Nietzsche&rsquo;s <em>The Birth of Tragedy</em>. Benjamin
claims that <em>The Birth of Tragedy</em> substantiates the critical
insight that the empathy of undirected modern feeling is unhelpful for
properly grasping ancient tragedy (OGT, 93). Instead, Nietzsche
undertook a metaphysical inquiry into the essence of tragedy as a
dialectical interplay of the contrasting aesthetic impulses of
Apollonian semblance and Dionysian truth. This dialectic is central to
Benjamin&rsquo;s own philosophical investigations, particularly his
claim&mdash;derived from his discussion of Goethe&rsquo;s <em>Elective
Affinities</em>&mdash;that an expressionless moment is constitutive of
art, in which the limits of semblance are broached precisely in order
to illuminate an artistic truth.</p>

<p>
But Benjamin is also critical of Nietzsche for restricting his
approach to aesthetics, and therefore renouncing the understanding of
tragedy in historical terms. Lacking a philosophy of history,
Nietzsche&rsquo;s study was unable to situate the political and
ethical significance of the metaphysical and mythical features it
isolates (OGT, 93). Influenced by ideas from Franz Rosenzweig and
Florens Christian Rang (Asman 1992), Benjamin presents tragedy as
expressing a perceived break between the prehistorical age of mythical
gods and heroes and the emergence of a new ethical and political
community. The historical limitations of Nietzsche&rsquo;s theory of
tragedy become acute when it comes to the question of the possibility
of a recuperation of the tragic form in modern theatre. Whilst
Nietzsche tends to simply denounce the weakness of modern drama
against the strength of the Greeks (excepting, in his early work, the
operas of Wagner), Benjamin is concerned with establishing whether the
historical conditions of the tragic form are themselves a limit to its
contemporary efficacy.</p>

<p>
In line with the principles of Romantic criticism discussed above,
mourning-plays contain their own distinct form and should be
criticised according to their own immanently discovered standards. The
&ldquo;content [<em>Gehalt</em>]&rdquo; and &ldquo;true object&rdquo;
of the baroque mourning-play is not, as it is in tragedy, myth but
rather historical life (OGT, 46). As with Goethe&rsquo;s borrowing of
the novella form, this content is in part derived from other aesthetic
structures, principally the eschatological focus of mediaeval
Christian literature: the Passion-Plays, Mystery-Plays and chronicles
whose historiography portrayed &ldquo;the whole of the course of
history, world history as salvation history&rdquo; (OGT, 65). But the
Lutheran renunciation of the Catholic emphasis upon good works, and
the secularizing tendency implicit in the naturalistic legal and
political philosophies of the 16th and 17th century (discussed in
relation to Carl Schmitt&rsquo;s theory of sovereignty) resulted in
the stripping bare of human value and significance from such history.
This tense, antinomical combination of transcendence and immanence
produces an uneasy hybrid, in which history&mdash;as a narrative of
the human march towards redemption on the Day of Judgement&mdash;loses
the eschatological certainty of its redemptive conclusion, and becomes
secularized into a mere natural setting for the profane struggle over
political power.</p>

<p>
In the second part of his thesis, Benjamin employs the concept of
allegory to expose the implicit eschatological structure of these
works. However, the first part utilises the distorting tension of this
structure to distinguish the specific and historically conspicuous
technique of the German baroque mourning-play. This concludes by
identifying sorrow or mourning (<em>Trauer</em>) as the predominant
mood inherent to its metaphysical structure, in contrast to the
suffering of tragedy. With the &ldquo;total secularization of the
historical in the state of creation&hellip;History passes into the
setting&rdquo; to become natural history (OGT, 81), whose attendant
cognition is a melancholic contemplation of things which derives
enigmatic satisfaction from its very recognition of their transience
and emptiness (OGT, 141). &ldquo;For all wisdom of the melancholic
hearkens to the deep&rdquo;, Benjamin claims: &ldquo;it is won from
immersion in the life of creaturely things, and nothing of the voice
of revelation reaches it. Everything to do with Saturn points into the
depths of the earth&rdquo; (OGT, 157).</p>

<p>
It should be briefly noted here that while Benjamin&rsquo;s
preoccupation with melancholy has been legitimately extended as a
leitmotif more broadly across the events of his own life and thought,
the <em>Trauerspiel</em> book&rsquo;s suggestion that the comic is the
&ldquo;essential inner side of mourning&rdquo; (OGT, 123) points to an
underdeveloped aspect of his philosophy, which nonetheless echoes his
claim that comic action is the shadow cast by the tragic (SW1, 206).
The claim, in the essay on &lsquo;Fate and Character&rsquo; (1921),
that within such a comic shadow a truer conception of natural
innocence and freedom may be discerned (SW1, 206) offers a counterpart
to absolutization of <em>Schuld</em> (guilt/debt) without atonement
that is produced by capitalism as a &ldquo;purely cultic
religion&rdquo; (SW1, 288) and the fatalism that follows, even for
Nietzsche, Marx and Freud (SW1, 289). Although this aspect of
Benjamin&rsquo;s thought has received relatively little attention
compared to his work on tragedy and mourning, it continues to inform,
for example, his physiognomies of &ldquo;left-wing melancholy&rdquo;
(SW2, 423&ndash;427) and &ldquo;the destructive character&rdquo; (SW2,
541&ndash;2), his positive evaluation of Chaplin&rsquo;s comedies and
Brecht&rsquo;s epic theatre, and the approach to radio plays in his
later writings (cf. Bontea 2006; Allen and Chari 2015; Feuer 2018 and
more broadly Feuer&rsquo;s blog
 <a href="https://schlemielintheory.com">https://schlemielintheory.com</a>;
 Barale 2019; Lewis 2020; Kolour 2023).</p>

<p>
To grasp how the form of these works are determined by their truth
content requires a reconstruction of the baroque concept of the
allegorical which structures its mood of melancholic
contemplativeness. Benjamin&rsquo;s claim is that a genuine
understanding of the allegorical as it emerged in its highest form in
the 17th century has been obscured by, on the one hand, the later
Romantic aestheticizing of the symbol and, on the other, by the
tendency to conceive the allegorical negatively in its contrast with
this devalued, aesthetic concept. It is only by first recovering a
genuine theological concept of the symbol, therefore, that we are able
in turn to distinguish an authentic concept of the allegorical. This
it to be done by reasserting the profound but paradoxical theological
unity between the material and the transcendental found in the
symbolic. The fundamental distinction between theological concepts of
symbol and the allegory will then be seen as concerning not their
differing objects (Idea vs. abstract concept), but the differing ways
in which they signify, express or represent this object. Benjamin will
conclude that this difference is, specifically, a temporal one.</p>

<p>
Drawing on undeveloped insights found in the work of the mythographers
Georg Friedrich Creuzer and Johann Joseph von G&ouml;rres, Benjamin
points out how &ldquo;the temporal measure for the experience of the
symbol[<em>Symbolerfahrung</em>] is the mystical instant
[<em>Nu</em>]&rdquo; (OGT, 173). We must understand the temporality of
the allegorical, in contrast, as something dynamic, mobile, and fluid.
This authentic concept of allegory arises in the 17th century baroque
as a response to the antithesis between mediaeval religiosity and
Renaissance secularization discussed earlier. The spatialization of
the temporal structure of eschatology in the allegorical corresponds
to the naturalization of the religious structure of history in the
baroque: &ldquo;Whereas in the symbol, with the sublimation of
downfall, the transfigured countenance of nature reveals itself
fleetingly in the light of salvation, in allegory there lies before
the eyes of the observer the <em>facies hippocratica</em> [lit.
&lsquo;Hippocratic face&rsquo; = the sunken, hollow and pinched
features exhibited by the dying] of history as petrified primal
landscape. History, in everything untimely, sorrowful, and miscarried
that belongs to it from the beginning, is inscribed in a
face&mdash;no, in a death&rsquo;s head [<em>Totenkopfe</em>]&rdquo;
(OGT, 174).</p>

<p>
From the perspective of the allegorical, the instantaneous
transformation within the symbolic becomes a natural history slowed to
such an extreme that every sign appears frozen and&mdash;seemingly
loosened from every other relationship&mdash;arbitrary. The concrete
corporeality of the written script exemplifies this allegorical
emphasis upon things. Allegory is not the <em>conventional</em>
representation of some expression, as misunderstood by later critics,
but an <em>expression</em> of convention [<em>Ausdruck der
Konvention</em>] (OGT, 185). Allegorical expression includes as its
object this very conventionality of the historical, this appearance of
insignificance and indifference. That is, convention itself comes to
be signified or expressed. What Benjamin rediscovers in the
allegorical is, then, something akin to the concept of the
expressionless, as the torso of a symbol, introduced in the essay on
Goethe. Benjamin argues that this predominance of the allegorical
viewpoint in the 17th century baroque finds it most dramatic
expression in the mourning-play, and that consequently the Idea of the
mourning-play must be grasped via the allegorical.</p>

<p>
The <em>Erkenntniskritische Vorrede</em> or &lsquo;Epistemo-Critical
Prologue&rsquo; to the work may be understood as having two central
functions: it provides a direct methodological justification for the
theory of criticism being utilised in the work, by way of a
problematization of existing disciplinary approaches, and it
implicitly recovers a concept of allegorical experience which is
delineated in the second part of the thesis in terms amenable for
modernity. At the level of methodology, Benjamin advocates the
necessity of a transdisciplinary approach (Osborne 2011, 24) to
artworks, capable of critically overcoming the epistemological and
historical limitations of the existing disciplines of the philosophy
of art and the history of art (specifically, literary history). This
transdisciplinary aspect of Benjamin&rsquo;s thesis may partially
account for the difficulties in its reception at the University of
Frankfurt, where the thesis was rejected by the departments of both
philosophy and literature. Much of the theoretical discussion in the
Prologue is concerned with correcting the methodological one-sidedness
of each existing approach by way of the positive features of the
other. In general, the philosophy of art correctly attends to the
problem of essences, but remains hampered by its lack of any adequate
historical consideration. Conversely, the history of art is
preoccupied with historical lineage but has no adequate concept of
essence. Yet it is not simply an amalgamation of aesthetics and
history that is required, but their radical rethinking in accordance
with first a historical concept of essence and second a philosophical
concept of history.</p>

<p>
Broadly speaking, Benjamin&rsquo;s theory of Ideas transposes the
philosophical problem of metaphysical realism into the context of
aesthetics. That is, it asks about the reality of aesthetic genres
such as &lsquo;tragedy&rsquo; or of artistic epochs such as the
&lsquo;Renaissance&rsquo; that classify a group of particular works
according to a set of common characteristics. The Prologue criticises
existing traditions of aesthetic nominalism for their inadequate
resolution of the problem. The uncritical use of inductive methods
demonstrated by literary historians rejects the hypostatization of
terms such as &ldquo;Renaissance&rdquo; on the grounds that it
promotes a false identity between similar empirical features, which
obscures their diversity. This aversion to any realism of constitutive
Ideas is grounded on the positivist criterion of factual verification.
A term like the &ldquo;Renaissance&rdquo; is consequently utilised by
them only on the proviso that it is understood as merely an abstract
general concept. This quickly leads to scepticism, however, since its
still fails to address the problematic criteria by which this general
concept is initially picked out and abstracted from the multiplicity
of particulars or on what grounds these particulars are grouped
together. Consequently, it fails to appreciate the necessity of the
Platonic postulation of Ideas for the representation of essences:
whilst concepts seek to make the similar identical, Ideas are
necessary to effect a dialectical synthesis between phenomenal
extremes (OGT, 18&ndash;19). In contrast, philosophers of art possess
a concern with the essential that ends up renouncing any notion of
generic forms, on the grounds that the singular originality of every
single work entails the only possible essential genre must be the
universal and individual one of art itself. The error&mdash;as
Benjamin had previously charged the Early German Romantics, discussed
above&mdash;is to dissolve real and important aesthetic structures or
forms into an undifferentiated unity (of art), which denies their
irreducible multiplicity (OGT, 21&ndash;23).</p>

<p>
The theory of Ideas presented in the Prologue is truncated and
difficult to understand outside the context of Benjamin&rsquo;s
earlier works, and the philosophical tradition that it engages with is
further obscured in the first English translation. However, the
critical aspects of Benjamin&rsquo;s investigation
advocate&mdash;against aesthetic versions of positivist
empiricism&mdash;a metaphysical realism, and, against certain versions
of philosophical idealism, a non-singular essentialism. That is, he
does not restrict the possibility of metaphysical reality only to
actual empirical particulars and he advocates the multiplicity and not
singularity of the essence (understood, in Goethean terms, as a
harmony and not a unity of truth). In doing so, he must address that
&lsquo;theological&rsquo; paradox, mentioned in the discussion of
symbol and allegory, of how the transcendental/supersensuous appears
immanently within the material/sensuous. Benjamin is clear that the
relation between Ideas and phenomenon is neither one of Aristotelian
&lsquo;containment&rsquo; nor one of Kantian lawfulness or hypothesis.
Ideas are not given to some intellectual intuition, but they are
capable of being sensuously represented. Such a sensuous
representation of the truth remains the task of philosophy.</p>

<p>
Benjamin&rsquo;s theoretical elaboration proceeds by startling
imagistic reconfigurations of pre-existing elements within the
philosophical tradition. He offers a number of possibilities for
thinking such Ideas in the Prologue, taken from the realm not only of
philosophy but of aesthetics, theology and science. The first is the
Platonic Idea, here divorced from its association with the scientific
ascent to some purely rational, objective knowledge (such as appears
in the account of dialectic in the <em>Republic</em>) and instead
linked to the discussion of beautiful semblance in the
<em>Symposium</em> (OGT, 6). The second is that of the Adamic Name, as
developed in his earlier theory of language. In this context, he
comments that the Early German Romantics were frustrated in their
attempt to renew the theory of Ideas because truth took on the
character of reflective consciousness for them, rather than that
intentionless, linguistic character in which things were subsumed
under essential Names by Adam&rsquo;s primal-interrogation
[<em>urvernehmen</em>] (OGT, 15). Naming is the primal history
[<em>Urgeschicte</em>] of signifying, indicating a thing-like
disinterest which contrasts with the directed, unifying intentionality
of Husserlian phenomenology (OGT, 14). The third is the Goethean
Ideal, which is recalled here in the context of the Faustian
&ldquo;Mothers&rdquo; and which implicitly gestures towards his
earlier discussions of Goethe (OGT, 11). Finally, and most famously,
Benjamin compares the virtual objectivity of the Idea represented
through the reconfiguring of actual phenomena to an astrological
constellation, which simultaneously groups together and is revealed by
the cluster of individual stars (OGT, 11). Truth is said to be
&ldquo;actualized in the round dance of presented Ideas
[<em>vergegenw&auml;rtigt im Reigen der dargestellen
Ideen</em>]&rdquo; (OGT, 4). This concept of the constellation is
taken up directly in Adorno&rsquo;s inaugural lecture &lsquo;The
Actuality of Philosophy&rsquo;, where he speaks of &lsquo;the
manipulation of conceptual material by philosophy&hellip;of grouping
and trial arrangement, of constellation and construction&rsquo;
(Adorno 1931, 131). It comes to inform Benjamin&rsquo;s philosophical
practice in his major writings from this point onwards, from
<em>One-Way Street</em> (1928), via the methodological demand for the
construction of history and the attendant theory of the dialectical
image in his work related to the &ldquo;Arcades Project&rdquo; in the
1930s, through to the concept of history presented in his celebrated
late essay, &lsquo;On the Concept of History&rsquo; (1940).</p>

<p>
Benjamin&rsquo;s concern to reincorporate the perspective of
art&rsquo;s temporal transformation demands an analogous
radicalization. The &ldquo;genetic and concrete classification&rdquo;
(OGT, 24) that Benedetto Croce called history (in order to distinguish
it from that generalizing thought that abstracts away from change and
development) must now be reconciled with Benjamin&rsquo;s theory of
Ideas. For the messianic philosophy of history that grounds
Benjamin&rsquo;s work problematizes existing formulations of the
concepts of history and historical origin. In line with his discussion
of the Idea, the concept of historical origin should not be reduced to
the causality and actuality of the empirically factual, nor should it
be regarded as a purely logical and timeless essence. It is not
merely, Benjamin argues, &ldquo;the coming-to-be of what has
originated&rdquo; and cannot be recognized in &ldquo;the naked,
manifest existence of the factual&rdquo; (OGT, 24). For the
&lsquo;historical&rsquo; sequence that permits the Idea to be
represented must include not only that of the actual phenomena of a
given period, but also that of their subsequent development in the
understanding of later epochs. An investigation of the essence of the
German mourning-play, for example, cannot restrict itself to
contemporaneous events and actual plays as if these were
&lsquo;facts&rsquo; settled and decided once and for all, but must
also investigate the changing understanding of this historical epoch
and the varying reception of these plays, including the prior
conditions of its own self-understanding. But nor is it a
&ldquo;purely logical&rdquo; category, as if the Idea were some
essence detached from and unrelated to history, to be grasped through
an abstraction from all these particular historical developments (OGT,
25). Origin [<em>Ursprung</em>] is therefore distinguished from a
merely genetic coming-into-being [<em>Enstehung</em>] and evolutionary
development of &lsquo;pure history&rsquo;, to include the essential
inner history of the &ldquo;life of the works and forms&rdquo; (OGT,
24&ndash;6). The &ldquo;science of the Origin&rdquo; is a
philosophical history, a history of the essential, whose contemplation
enlists a dialectical perspective to grasp the form of the
&ldquo;original phenomenon&rdquo;: as something subject to a process
of becoming and disappearing, and therefore only partial and
incomplete. Benjamin once again resorts to an image: &ldquo;The origin
stands as eddy in the stream of becoming and vigorously draws the
emerging material into its rhythm&rdquo; (OGT, 24). Criticism attempts
to virtually reassemble the fore- and after-history [<em>Vor- und
Nachgeschichte</em>] of the phenomena into a historical constellation,
in which the Idea is represented and the phenomena redeemed. This is
its messianic function in relation to the historical Absolute.</p>

<p>
The Prologue also seeks to rescue the allegorical experience
recognised in the mourning-plays for a modern theory of criticism.
Allegorical contemplation aims at the ruination of things so that it
can, in its redemptive moment, construct [<em>baun</em>] a new whole
out of the elements of the old. The character of this construction
distinguishes it from the creative invention of fantasy, since it
manipulates and rearranges pre-existing material. To leave an imprint
or impression of this construction [<em>Konstruktion</em>] is one of
its aims. This dual emphasis upon destruction and construction has led
a number of scholars to see an anticipation of Derridean
deconstruction in Benjamin&rsquo;s work (Fischer 1996, Section 1:
Modernity/Postmodernity; Weber 2008, 122&ndash;128), although it
should be noted that his consideration of the specific historicity of
this concept of criticism and his insistence of the immanent truth
content of artworks remains resolutely modernist, and cannot be easily
assimilated into any &lsquo;postmodernist&rsquo; position (cf. Weigel
1996, xiv). The underlying affinity between romanticism and the
baroque lies in their shared modernist concern with correcting
classicism in art and the quasi-mythical perspective of classicism in
general (OGT, 230; 185). The Prologue reflects upon this
&lsquo;modernity&rsquo; of the baroque when it notes how the
&ldquo;Striking analogies to the current state of German literature
have repeatedly given rise to &hellip;immersion in the Baroque&rdquo;
(OGT, 36). Although Benjamin is citing the similarities between
Expressionism in modern literature and the Mannerist exaggeration of
the baroque, his own reconstruction of allegorical experience and its
value for aesthetic theory is experienced according to a historical
conjunction between the baroque past and the modernity of
Benjamin&rsquo;s present: modernity both reveals and is revealed in
the baroque.</p>

<h2><a id="Politics">5. Politics</a></h2>

<p>
If the book on <em>Trauerspiel</em> (originating 1916, written
1923&ndash;1925, published 1928) concluded Benjamin&rsquo;s German
&ldquo;cycle of production&rdquo; (C, 322), a new cycle was initiated
with <em>One-Way Street</em> (<em>Einbahnstra&szlig;e</em>) (written
1923&ndash;6, published 1928), whose form and content puts into
practice that speculative concept of experience, with its allegorical
immersion into the depths of things. The city furnishes the sensuous,
imagistic material for <em>One-Way Street</em>, whilst the genres of
the leaflet, placard and advertisement provide the constructive
principle by which it is rearranged as a constellation. This formal
methodology resembles the technological media of photography and film,
as well as the avant-garde practices of Russian Constructivism and
French Surrealism. This involves what Adorno described as a
&ldquo;philosophy directed against philosophy&rdquo; (Adorno 1955,
235) or what Howard Caygill calls Benjamin&rsquo;s
&ldquo;philosophizing beyond philosophy&rdquo; (Caygill 1998,
120).</p>

<p>
The overlap and transition between these two cycles is visible in the
contrast between Benjamin&rsquo;s reflections on sovereign violence in
the sixteenth century in the <em>Trauerspiel</em> book and his
discussion of contemporary revolutionary violence in his
&lsquo;Critique of Violence&rsquo; (1921), one of the few remaining
pieces from what was planned as a large-scale study of political
thought initiated at the turn of the 1920s (Steiner 2001, 61). The
latter included a number of lost pieces relating to &lsquo;the true
politics&rsquo; and a series of aphorisms that were eventually
transformed into <em>One-Way Street</em>, alongside the notes on
&lsquo;Capitalism as Religion,&rsquo; elements of which were also
incorporated into the latter (Fenves and Ng 2021, 16&ndash;17, 117,
304).</p>

<p>
The &lsquo;Critique of Violence&rsquo; demonstrates Benjamin&rsquo;s
continuing concern with the Kantian and post-Kantian philosophical
traditions, in particular Herman Cohen&rsquo;s attempt to synthesize
neo-Kantianism and Judaism in his <em>Ethics of Pure Will</em>. The
title under which the project as a whole was conceived, &lsquo;The
True Politics&rsquo;, was taken from Kant&rsquo;s essay on
<em>Perpetual Peace</em> and the title of a planned chapter,
&lsquo;Teleology without Final Purpose,&rsquo; alludes to Kant&rsquo;s
discussions of aesthetic and teleological judgements in the
<em>Critique of the Power of Judgment</em> (Fenves and Ng 2021,
18&ndash;19). But it also shows Benjamin&rsquo;s &ldquo;turn to
political thought&rdquo; (GB, 2:60) in the tumultuous post-war period,
just prior to his more sustained encounter with Marxism via
Gy&ouml;rgy Luk&aacute;cs&rsquo;s <em>History and Class
Consciousness</em> and the Soviet theatre director Asja Lacis, on the
island of Capri in 1924. The project therefore marks both a continuity
with and a break from what Irving Wohlfarth has called his earlier
&ldquo;politics of Youth&rdquo; (Wohlfarth 1992, 164). If, as Benjamin
remarks, his break from the Youth Movement did not constitute the
abandonment of this earlier thought but its submergence into a
&ldquo;harder, purer, more invisible radicalism&rdquo; (C, 74), this
in part accounts for what Clark describes as the &lsquo;cryptic&rsquo;
character of the anthropological materialism of <em>The Arcades
Project</em>, where, Clark remarks, it is &ldquo;as if such a politics
were being actively aired and developed elsewhere&rdquo; (Clark 2003,
45&ndash;46).</p>

<p>
In part because of its singular place within this largely lost
project, in part because its neglect for many years, and in part
because of its own ambiguous construction, the &lsquo;Critique of
Violence [<em>Gewalt</em>]&rsquo; has recently come to acquire an
important role in the reception of Benjamin&rsquo;s work and a
&ldquo;canonic status in radical political theory and
philosophy&rdquo; more generally (Greenberg 2008, 324). The immediate
context of Benjamin&rsquo;s essay relates to the general strike of
March 1920, which had defeated an attempted military coup against the
social democratic coalition that had come to government in the wake of
the 1918 revolution. In September that year, in the context of a
discussion of the coup, the journal <em>Bl&auml;tter f&uuml;r
Reli&ouml;sen Sozialismus</em> published a juridical analysis of the
legal right to the use of <em>Gewalt</em>, which started from the
hypothesis that only the state has such a right, a position Benjamin
opposes.</p>

<p>
As the range of examples Benjamin includes in his response demonstrate
&ndash; strike action, martial law, conscription, capital punishment,
legal contracts, legal rights, police power, warfare, revolutions,
mythical violence and divine judgement &ndash; the term
<em>Gewalt</em> indicates power, force or authority as well as the
physical violence that is employed to preserve it or to challenge it.
Because, for Benjamin, the concept is closely connected to the spheres
of law and justice, it also concerns the coercive or uncoercive
relationship between means and ends. Benjamin&rsquo;s examples seek to
reveal the various ways in which violence and law comingle as either
&lsquo;lawmaking [<em>rechtsetzende</em>]&rsquo; or
&lsquo;law-preserving [<em>rechtserhaltende</em>]&rsquo; force, as
well as the ways the state insists on the separation and distinction
between them in order to conceal its own monopolization of violence.
In strike action, for example, the &ldquo;moment of violence&hellip;
is necessarily introduced, in the form of extortion &hellip;if it
takes place in the context of a conscious readiness to resume the
suspended action under certain circumstances that either have nothing
whatever to do with this action or only superficially modify it&rdquo;
(SW1, 239). The state concedes the right to strike &ndash; and thus
interposes legal means and ends for such coercion &ndash; under such
circumstances because &ldquo;it forestalls violent actions the state
is afraid to oppose&rdquo; (SW1, 245). In this way, even a general
strike (as with the general strike of March 1920) can function to
establish and to preserve the law of the state. Khatib (2017, 616) has
extended Benjamin&rsquo;s example of the conflation of lawmaking and
law-preserving in police violence to global practices of colonialism,
imperialism, and post-colonial legality under the conditions of the
capitalist world market. Benjamin concludes that it cannot be a
question of the ends pursued that invalidates violence in such
instances but rather that the use of force by individuals is in itself
an existential threat to the functioning of the law and its
institutions.</p>

<p>
To avoid the circularity that follows when the legitimacy of using
force is analysed only in relation to the ends pursued (since these
ends have been determined by the state that has, historically,
utilized violence as a means to its possession of power), Benjamin
seeks to develop a critical analysis of <em>Gewalt</em> that considers
its ethical legitimacy as a means, independent of any ends pursued.
Conflating both coercive forms of lawmaking and law-preserving
violence together as forms of mythic violence, Benjamin seeks to
deduce and so justify the possibility of an ethical use of violence
that is distinct from all mythical inauguration of power and so
identified as law-destroying force. In Kantian terms, the
&lsquo;Critique of Violence&rsquo; deduces such a possibility through
the postulation of divine violence whose expiatory power, because it
is connected to a higher sphere of justice rather than the law, cannot
be known within human history. Only the assurance of such divine
violence &ldquo;furnishes proof that revolutionary violence, the
highest manifestation of unalloyed violence by humans, is possible,
and shows by what means&rdquo; (SW1, 252).</p>

<p>
Drawing on the French political theorist Georges Sorel&rsquo;s
<em>Reflections on Violence</em>, Benjamin delineates the proletarian
or <em>revolutionary</em> general strike from the <em>political</em>
strike in the following terms: while the first form of interruption of
work is a &lsquo;violent&rsquo; and law-making means, since it takes
place in readiness to resume work under the modified conditions it
demands of those in power, the second is a nonviolent and anarchistic
&ldquo;pure means&rdquo; (SW1, 246). Benjamin&rsquo;s position does
not deny a moral right to use violence as such but does deny it
&ldquo;to every human institution, community, or individuality that
either claims a monopoly over it or in any way claims that right for
itself&rdquo; (SW1, 232). Proyschyn (2014, 397) has suggested
Benjamin&rsquo;s account of the revolutionary general strike is
prescient of post-industrial politics, with the decline of union
militancy and the rise of occupations.</p>

<p>
The afterlives of Benjamin&rsquo;s &lsquo;Critique of Violence&rsquo;
represent attempts to wrestle with the legacy of such a politics,
giving rise to divergent and at times controversial interpretations of
its project. The essay&rsquo;s suggestion that the conference or
parley [<em>Unterredung</em>], which induces individuals or states to
reconcile their interests peacefully without involving the legal
system (SW1, 247), isolates language as pure means wholly inaccessible
to the instrumentality of violence (SW1, 244&ndash;5) has led
J&uuml;rgen Habermas (1979, 59) to insist that the contemporary
relevance of Benjamin&rsquo;s thought lay not in its appeal to another
kind of force but in guiding &ldquo;a theory of linguistic
communication&rdquo; for &ldquo;a materialist theory of social
evolution&rdquo;. Moran and Salzani (2015, 3&ndash;4) have suggested
in turn that the problematic influence of Habermas&rsquo;s article
&ldquo;may have contributed to a kind of non-reading of
Benjamin&rsquo;s essay&rdquo; by later generations of critical
theorists.</p>

<p>
One early strand of the reception of Benjamin&rsquo;s essay, promoted
in particular by Giorgio Agamben, sought to situate his political
thought within the context of debates around political theology,
particularly the Catholic-infused political theology of Carl Schmitt.
This reception begins with Agamben&rsquo;s 1970 essay &lsquo;On the
Limits of Violence,&rsquo; which draws on Benjamin alongside
Arendt&rsquo;s <em>The Human Condition</em>. Agamben&rsquo;s essay is
contemporaneous with Arendt&rsquo;s <em>On Violence</em> and a
footnote referencing Agamben&rsquo;s essay was added to the German
edition, but it has become influential via the critique of the
biopolitical &lsquo;state of exception&rsquo; initiated by
Agamben&rsquo;s <em>Homo Sacer</em> (1995, trans. 1998) and <em>State
of Exception</em> (2003, trans. 2005). Agamben&rsquo;s popularization
of an intellectual encounter between Benjamin and Schmitt follows from
the critical recuperation of the latter by the religious philosopher
Jacob Taubes, alongside Taubes&rsquo;s claim that Benjamin&rsquo;s
connection to Judaism can only be understood according to the
political theology of Saint Paul. Despite Agamben&rsquo;s intention to
complete Benjamin&rsquo;s account of &lsquo;divine violence&rsquo; as
a critique of Schmitt&rsquo;s theory of sovereignty &ndash; with the
former, Agamben suggesting, managing to &ldquo;carefully stay a
hair&rsquo;s breadth away from it&rdquo; (Pomreneke 2017) &ndash;
there is little evidence to substantiate such a claim, which involves
a number of chronological reversals (Kostko 2008; Pomreneke 2017) and
overstates (Butler 2006, 206&ndash;7) or misreads Benjamin&rsquo;s
interest in Schmitt (Hamacher 1991, 1149, n.34; Tomba 2009,
131&ndash;132; Averlar 2005, 79&ndash;106; Weber 2008, 176&ndash;194).
In this respect, perhaps, it was not Schmitt&rsquo;s political
theology but the reactionary vitalism of Ludwig Klages that proved a
more influential and enduring object of fascination for Benjamin (Fuld
1981; McCole 1993, 178&ndash;180, 236&ndash;246; Wolin 1994,
xxxi&ndash;xxxviii; Wohlfarth 2002, 65&ndash;109; Lebovic 2013,
1&ndash;10, 79&ndash;110; Charles 2018, 52&ndash;62).</p>

<p>
An alternative reception of Benjamin&rsquo;s essay, reacting to the
concerns raised by these debates (Bredekamp 2016, 695), emphasized the
place of language and sought to reassert the centrality of a Judaic
conception of justice in his political thought, beginning with Jacques
Derrida&rsquo;s deconstruction of law in <em>The Force of Law: the
Mystical Foundation of Authority</em> (1990). Derrida&rsquo;s reading
recalls the &ldquo;moment in which the foundation [or revolutionary
moment] of law remains suspended in the void or over the abyss,
suspended by a pure performative act&hellip; before a law not yet
determined &hellip;a law yet to come&hellip; (in somewhat the same
sense that one speaks of a &lsquo;felicitous performative speech
act&rsquo;)&rdquo; (Derrida 1990, 36). Such a foundation points to how
the series of oppositions Benjamin draws in his essay &ndash;
law-making/law-preserving violence, mythic/divine violence, political
strike/proletarian general strike &ndash; deconstruct themselves
(Derrida 1990, 38), leaving the text unable to &ldquo;escape the law
that it states&rdquo; and a &ldquo;ruined and contaminated
&hellip;.specter of itself&rdquo; (Derrida 1990, 42&ndash;3). Derrida
worries this undecidability in Benjamin&rsquo;s
&lsquo;messianico-Marxist&rsquo; justification of divine violence
could be used to legitimate antiparliamentary sentiments and the
violence of political events such as the Holocaust (although
&ldquo;Derrida gives no supporting evidence for this claim&rdquo;) and
so, against the &ldquo;all-too-strong Messianism&rdquo; of
Benjamin&rsquo;s essay, he recovers a &lsquo;messianicity&rsquo;
&ldquo;weaker even than the &lsquo;weak messianic force&rsquo; of the
[later] &lsquo;Theses&rsquo;&rdquo; (Wohlfarth 2008&ndash;9, 2:15).
Derrida&rsquo;s subsequent <em>Spectres of Marx</em> (1993) extends
this figure of spectrality to the messianicity of Marxism more
generally.</p>

<p>
Against the receptions of Benjamin&rsquo;s politics outlined above,
the messianic would rather appear to point to the &ldquo;irreducible
theological remainder&rdquo; upon which Benjamin&rsquo;s concept of
redemption rests, one that Khatib (2013) argues should not be reduced
to that of Judaeo-Christian theology. The construction of
Benjamin&rsquo;s politics, as it develops from the &lsquo;Critique of
Violence&rsquo; and &lsquo;Capitalism as Religion&rsquo; through
<em>One-Way Street</em> and the <em>Arcades Project</em>, is better
historically contextualized against the totalizing experience of
capitalist modernity. For Benjamin, the religious structure of
capitalism is identified as that of a cult without theology, i.e. one
that &ldquo;makes guilt pervasive&rdquo; (SW1, 289) but offers no
possibility of &ldquo;conversion, purification, and penance&rdquo;
(SW1, 289&ndash;290) and so is &ldquo;<em>sans tr&ecirc;ve et sans
merci</em>&rdquo; [&ldquo;without truce and without mercy&rdquo;:
likely a paraphrase of Baudelaire&rsquo;s description in &lsquo;<em>Le
Cr&eacute;puscule du soir</em>&rsquo; of the criminality of the Paris
night as &ldquo;<em>ni tr&ecirc;ve ni merci</em>&rdquo; but
mistranscribed in GS as &ldquo;<em>r&ecirc;ve</em>&rdquo; and so
mistranslated in SW1 as &ldquo;dream&rdquo;]. The philosophically
conceived relation between theology and politics, for Benjamin, is
that of a destructiveness he names nihilism (GS 2.1:204) and justifies
through a divine force that cannot provide any profane foundation,
certainly not a theocratic one, and can have no claim on domination
(SW1, 227).</p>

<p>
While Benjamin&rsquo;s political thought may be situated in the milieu
of Expressionist Nietzsche-reception (Steiner 2001), including that of
Erich Unger, his &ldquo;definition of politics&rdquo; as &ldquo;the
fulfillment of an unimproved/unelevated humanness [<em>die
Erf&uuml;llung der ungestiegerten Menschhaftigkeit</em>]&rdquo;(SW1,
227; trans. Fenves &amp; Ng 2021, 83) simultaneously barricades itself
against not only any liberal or enlightenment ideal of progress but
also against any Nietzschean-inspired politics of the
<em>&Uuml;bermensch</em>. For Benjamin, Nietzsche&rsquo;s idea of the
<em>&Uuml;bermensch</em> is &ldquo;the first to recognize the religion
of capitalism&hellip;. characterized (even for Nietzsche himself) by
guilt [<em>Schuld</em>] in a religious sense&rdquo; and &ldquo;begin
to bring it to fulfillment [<em>zu erf&uuml;llen</em>]&rdquo; (SW1,
289). But what Nietzsche in <em>Ecco Home</em> calls his
&lsquo;<em>great politics</em>&rsquo; promises such fulfilment only by
transposing &ldquo;the apocalyptic &lsquo;leap&rsquo; [of theology]
&hellip;into an&hellip;explosive and discontinuous elevation
[<em>Steigerung</em>]&rdquo;: &ldquo;a breaking open of the heavens by
an elevated humanness [<em>gesteigerte Menschhaftigkeit</em>]&rdquo;
(SW1, 289; trans amended). In contrast to Nietzsche&rsquo;s own
critique of bourgeois humanism (Charles 2013; Lopez 2022) &ndash; and
in a subversive appropriation of fascism&rsquo;s own antisemitic and
anti-communist pejoratives &ndash; Benjamin in the 1930s emphasizes
the radical potential of the <em>Unmensch</em> (SW2, 447) and of a
&ldquo;new, positive concept of barbarism&rdquo; (SW2, 732),
encapsulated in the figures of Mickey Mouse, Fourier&rsquo;s utopian
fantasies, Scheerbert&rsquo;s intergalactic creatures, and
Klee&rsquo;s monstrous <em>Angelus Novus</em>. Such a
&ldquo;definition of politics&rdquo; continues to inform what Benjamin
later calls &ldquo;the two articles of my
&lsquo;politics&rsquo;&rdquo;, defined in the <em>Arcades Project</em>
as &ldquo;the idea of revolution as an innervation of the technical
organs of the collective&rdquo; and &ldquo;the idea of the
&lsquo;cracking open [<em>Aufknacken</em>] of natural
teleology&rsquo;&rdquo; (AP W7,4). This is an idea of collective
bodily revolution that establishes the terms on which Benjamin
negotiates his relationship to Marxism in the coming years, outlining
the contours of what Adorno will later term his
&ldquo;anthropological&rdquo; &ndash; rather than a reductively
economic or &ldquo;orthodox&rdquo; &ndash; materialism.</p>

<p>
The presentation of contemporary capitalism as metropolitan modernity
in <em>One-Way Street</em> also marks the turning point in
Benjamin&rsquo;s writings, away from what he retrospectively called
&ldquo;an archaic form of philosophizing naively caught up in
nature&rdquo; (BA, 88) towards the development of &ldquo;a political
view of the past&rdquo; (SW 2, 210). The theory of experience outlined
in his early writings is enlisted for revolutionary ends. In the
essay, &lsquo;Surrealism: The Last Snapshot of the European
Intelligentsia&rsquo; (1929), Surrealist experience provides an
example of a &ldquo;profane illumination&rdquo;, which in contrast to
the sacred and moralistic kind found in religion was guided by a
political and a &ldquo;materialistic, anthropological
inspiration&rdquo; (SW 2, 209). The latent energy residing in the most
destitute and outmoded of things is, through the construction of new
political constellations, transformed into an intoxicating,
revolutionary experience (SW 2, 210). The possibility of such a
profane illumination of nineteenth century Paris, to be presented as
the origin of modernity, preoccupied the remaining decade of
Benjamin&rsquo;s life, and his research for the monumental and
unfinished <em>Arcades Project</em> provides the material from which
all his remaining work is constructed.</p>

<h2><a id="ArcPro">6. The Arcades Project</a></h2>

<p>
The city was the seedbed of Benjamin&rsquo;s &lsquo;gothic&rsquo;
Marxism (Cohen 1993); Paris its testing ground. All of
Benjamin&rsquo;s writings from the autumn of 1927 until his death in
1940 relate in one way or other to his great unfinished study
&lsquo;Paris&mdash;Capital of the Nineteenth Century&rsquo;, otherwise
known as <em>The Arcades Project</em> (<em>Das Passagen-Werk</em>),
after its founding image, taken by Benjamin from the 1926 novel,
<em>Le Paysan de Paris</em>, by the French surrealist Louis Aragon.
This was a book of which Benjamin wrote: &ldquo;I could never read
more than two or three pages in bed at night before my heart started
to beat so strongly that I had to lay the book aside.&rdquo; (BA, 88)
The arcades would become just one of five or six archetypal images of
the psychosocial space of 19th-century Paris around which the project
was organized&mdash;each paired with a particular, thematically
representative individual. But it provided the model for the others,
and its surrealist origin and liminal utopian impulse, neither quite
inside nor out, established the wish-image and the
dream-image&mdash;on the threshold of sleeping and waking&mdash;at the
heart of a work that was initially conceived as a kind of
&lsquo;dialectical fairytale&rsquo;. (The figure with whom &lsquo;the
arcades&rsquo; was paired was the utopian socialist Charles Fourier.)
All of Benjamin&rsquo;s major essays of the 1930s derived their
impetus and orientation from his Arcades work, and served to defer its
completion in the act of elaborating its elements.</p>

<p>
This deferral was also, in part, the result of a process of
maturation&mdash;a kind of ripening&mdash;immanent to the work itself.
<em>The Arcades</em> was a vast and ambitious project, not simply in
terms of the mass and breadth of its archival sources (sought out by
Benjamin in the Biblioth&egrave;que Nationale in Paris), but
also&mdash;indeed, primarily&mdash;with respect to its philosophical
and historical intent, and the methodological and representational
challenges it posed. Its sprawling, yet minutely investigated
historical object was to act as the point of entry into the
philosophically comprehended experience of metropolitan
capitalism&mdash;not some past experience, or the experience of a past
phase of capitalist development, but the experience of the capitalist
metropolis in Benjamin&rsquo;s own day&mdash;through the construction
of a specific series of relations between its elements
&lsquo;then&rsquo; and &lsquo;now&rsquo;. The practice of research,
conceptual organization and presentation that it involved was
self-consciously conceived as a working model for a new,
philosophically oriented, materialist historiography with political
intent. Its final, fragmentary and &lsquo;ruined&rsquo; status has
come to stand not simply as the sign of a failure of completion, but
as a paradigm of a form of constitutive incompletion that is
characteristic of all systematically oriented knowledge under the
conditions of modernity. In this respect, in its very failure to be
actualized, it confirmed the fundamental historical and philosophical
truth of Benjamin&rsquo;s earlier analysis of the Romantic
fragment&mdash;extending the genre in a hitherto unimagined way.</p>

<p>
In the ebb and flow of its changing rhythms&mdash;additions,
revisions, reformulations and retrievals&mdash;Benjamin&rsquo;s
<em>Arcades Project</em> provides an extraordinary case study in the
labour of conceptual construction via the configuration and
reconfiguration of archival materials. The voluminous &lsquo;Notes and
Materials&rsquo; that make up the <em>Arcades</em> as it has come down
to us remained unpublished until 1982, finally appearing in English
only in 1999 (GS V; AP). Only since their publication has it been
possible to get a clear sense of the overall trajectory of
Benjamin&rsquo;s thought during this period&mdash;rendering redundant,
or at least displacing, many of the polemics associated with previous
cycles of reception. The notes and materials are organized into
twenty-six alphabetically designated &lsquo;convolutes&rsquo;
(literally &lsquo;bundles&rsquo;) or folders, thematically defined by
various <em>objects</em> (arcades, catacombs, barricades, iron
constructions, mirrors, modes of lighting&hellip;), <em>topics</em>
(fashion, boredom, theory of knowledge, theory of progress, painting,
conspiracies&hellip;), <em>figures</em> (the collector, the flaneur,
the automaton&hellip;), <em>authors</em> (Baudelaire, Fourier, Jung,
Marx, Saint-Simon&hellip;) and their combinations. The project as a
whole received two &lsquo;expos&eacute;s&rsquo; or summaries, in 1935
and 1939 (the second, in French). However, its scope and theoretical
ambition&mdash;nothing less than a philosophical construction of
&ldquo;the primal history of the nineteenth century&rdquo; (BA,
90)&mdash;joined with the circumstances of Benjamin&rsquo;s life in
exile (the constant need to earn money by writing and the uncertainty
of a publisher for the project) to frustrate its realization. The only
lengthy segment of completed text derives from the part devoted to
Baudelaire (one of five parts in the 1939 expos&eacute;, cut down from
six in the initial 1935 version): the second of its three projected
sections, &lsquo;The Paris of the Second Empire in
Baudelaire&rsquo;&mdash;although even this was never published in
Benjamin&rsquo;s lifetime. However, the central chapter of this
section, &lsquo;The Flaneur&rsquo;, was revised and expanded (in part,
in response to an exchange of letters with Adorno) into the essay
&lsquo;Some Motifs in Baudelaire&rsquo;, which was published in the
Institute&rsquo;s journal, <em>Zeitschrift f&uuml;r
Sozialforschung</em> (<em>Journal for Social Research</em>) in January
1940. A powerful compressed draft of material corresponding to the
final section, on the commodity as a poetic object, exists as
&lsquo;Central Park&rsquo; (SW 4, 161&ndash;199). As the project
evolved, and in response to the barriers to its realization,
Baudelaire thus became increasingly central to Benjamin&rsquo;s
thinking. (&lsquo;Convolute J&rsquo;, on Baudelaire, is by far the
longest of the convolutes.) Encouraged by Horkheimer, Benjamin planned
to publish the material on Baudelaire as a separate book, to be
entitled, <em>Charles Baudelaire: A Lyric Poet in the Era of High
Capitalism</em>. The development of this process, whereby a primal
history of the nineteenth century gradually morphed into a book on
Baudelaire and &lsquo;high capitalism&rsquo;, may be represented,
diagrammatically, as follows.</p>

<blockquote>

