</blockquote>

<p>
However, to reduce the project to its own, restricted <em>de
facto</em> trajectory, rich as it is, does too much violence to the
historical and philosophical framework it embodies, from which the
material on Baudelaire gains its broader significance. The overarching
historical framework is that of capitalist modernity as a
&lsquo;crisis of experience&rsquo;. (The two terms, capitalism and
modernity, are inextricable for Benjamin in the context of 19th- and
early 20th-century Europe.) The founding problematic of
Benjamin&rsquo;s thought&mdash;the expansion of the Kantian concept of
experience, to infinity&mdash;is thus here provided with a concretely
historical context, in which the notion of infinity/absoluteness
becomes associated with the concept of history itself. The problem: to
dialectically redeem the concept of experience [<em>Erfahrung</em>] by
finding an appropriate way of experiencing the crisis of experience
itself. In classically &lsquo;modern&rsquo; terms, the present is
defined as a time of crisis and transition, and philosophical
experience (truth) is associated with the glimpse within the present,
via the past, of a utopian political future that would bring history
to an end. More immediately, the crisis is given political meaning by
two possible resolutions: the one destructive; the other constructive/
emancipatory&mdash;fascism and communism, respectively. In this
respect, for all his theoretical heterodoxy as a &lsquo;Marxist&rsquo;
and his philosophical affinities with Adorno, Benjamin was in search
of, and in solidarity with, new forms of collectivity connected to a
communist future. Herein lay the basis of his friendship with Brecht.
Unlike Brecht, however, he conceived them within the terms of a
speculative cultural history (Caygill 2004).</p>

<p>
Within this framework, three distinct strands of work (discussed in
the next three sections) can be discerned: (1) investigation of the
crisis of experience via the &lsquo;crisis of the arts&rsquo; (SW 2,
212) through the interrelated terms of <em>technology/technique</em>
[<em>Technik</em>], <em>aura</em>, <em>reproducibility</em>, and
<em>collectivity</em>; (2) philosophical distillation of the formal
structure of the experience of the new, and its historical and
political contradictions, out of its social forms, and the examination
of its relations to allegory and commodity-form; (3) construction of a
new historiography and a new philosophical concept of history. The
first may be traced through a linked series of essays of which
&lsquo;Surrealism: The Last Snapshot of the European
Intelligentsia&rsquo; (1929), &lsquo;Little History of
Photography&rsquo; (1931), &lsquo;The Work of Art in the Age of its
Technical Reproducibility&rsquo; (1935&ndash;9) and &lsquo;The
Storyteller&rsquo; (1936) are the most important. The second is
concentrated in readings of Baudelaire and related texts by Nietzsche
and Blanqui. (The focusing-in on these three thinkers is a focusing-in
on the relationship of capitalism to modernity in its purest,
nihilistic form). The third is conjured from a reflective conjunction
of Marx, Nietzsche and Surrealism. It takes methodological form in
&lsquo;Convolute N [On the Theory of Knowledge, Theory of
Progress]&rsquo; in <em>The Arcades Project</em> and achieved its
accidentally definitive presentation in Benjamin&rsquo;s most
frequently cited, but still fiercely interpretatively disputed text
(Caygill 2004; L&ouml;wy 2005; Tiedemman 1989; Wohlfarth 1978): the
fragments&mdash;known as theses&mdash;&lsquo;On the Concept of
History&rsquo;.</p>

<h2><a id="ArtTec">7. Art and Technology</a></h2>

<p>
That Benjamin approached the symptomatic significance of the
&lsquo;crisis of the arts&rsquo; for the &lsquo;crisis of
experience&rsquo; through the concept of <em>Technik</em> attests to
the fundamentally Marxist character of his conception of historical
development. It is the development of the forces of production that is
the motor of history. However, Benjamin was no more orthodox a Marxist
about technology than he was with regard to the concept of progress,
the Marxist version of which the German Social Democratic Party (SPD)
grounded upon it (see Section 8, below). Not only did he recognize the
potential for a &ldquo;bloodbath&rdquo; in a technology subjected to
&ldquo;the lust for profit&rdquo; (SW 1, 487)&mdash;amply demonstrated
in the horrors of the First World War&mdash;but he came to distinguish
between a &lsquo;first&rsquo; and a &lsquo;second&rsquo;, potentially
liberatory technology, the latter making possible &ldquo;a highly
productive use of the human being&rsquo;s self-alienation&rdquo; (SW
3, 107; 113). It appears, in places, as the basis for a kind of
&lsquo;technological cosmopolitics&rsquo; or politics of a &lsquo;new
collective technoid body&rsquo; (Caygill 2005, 225; Leslie 2000, 153,
in Osborne 2005, II: 391).</p>

<blockquote>

<p>
The mastery of nature, so the imperialists teach, is the purpose of
all technology [<em>Technik</em>]. But &hellip;technology is not the
mastery of nature but of the relation between nature and humanity.
&hellip;In technology a <em>physis</em> is being organized through
which mankind&rsquo;s contact with the cosmos takes a new and
different form from that which it had in nations
[<em>V&ouml;lkern</em>] and families. (SW 1, 487, translation
amended)</p>

<p>
The collective is a body, too. And the <em>physis</em> that is being
organized for it in technology can, through all its political and
factual reality, only be produced in that image sphere to which
profane illumination initiates us. Only when in technology body and
image so interpenetrate that all revolutionary tension becomes bodily
collective innervation, and all the bodily innervations of the
collective become revolutionary discharge, has reality transcended
itself to the extent demanded by the <em>Communist Manifesto</em>. (SW
2, 217&ndash;8)</p>
</blockquote>

<p>
These passages, from the concluding sections of <em>One-Way
Street</em> and the &lsquo;Surrealism&rsquo; essay, respectively,
convey something of the ecstatic character of Benjamin&rsquo;s
political thought at the outset of the 1930s, in which technology
appears on a political knife-edge between its possibilities as
&ldquo;a fetish of doom&rdquo; and &ldquo;a key to happiness&rdquo;
(SW 2, 321). Art&mdash;an art of the masses&mdash;appears within this
scenario as the educative mechanism through which the body of the
collective can begin to appropriate its own technological
potential.</p>

<blockquote>
The first technology really sought to master nature, whereas the
second aims rather at an interplay between nature and humanity. The
primary social function of art today is to rehearse that interplay.
This applies especially to film. <em>The function of film is to train
human beings in the apperception and reactions needed to deal with a
vast apparatus whose role in their lives is expanding almost
daily</em>. Dealing with this apparatus also teaches them that
technology will release them from their enslavement to the powers of
the apparatus only when humanity&rsquo;s whole constitution has
adapted itself to the new productive forces which the second
technology has set free. (SW 3, 107&ndash;8)
</blockquote>

<p>
In his footnote to this passage from the second version of &lsquo;The
Work of Art in the Age of its Technical Reproducibility&rsquo;
(&lsquo;<em>Das Kunstwerk im Zeitalter seiner technischen
Reproduzierbarkeit</em>&rsquo;, 1936), Benjamin refers us to the
&lsquo;phalansteries&rsquo;, the &ldquo;self-contained agrarian
collectives&rdquo; of Fourier&rsquo;s socialist utopia. In the Fourier
convolute of the <em>Arcades Project</em>, these are compared to the
two main articles of Benjamin&rsquo;s politics: &ldquo;the idea of
revolution as an innervation of the technical organs of the
collective&hellip; and the idea of the &lsquo;cracking open of natural
teleology&rsquo;&rdquo; (AP, [W7, 4], 631). For Benjamin, art, in the
form of film&mdash;the &ldquo;unfolding &lt;result&gt; of all the
forms of perception, the tempos and rhythms, which lie preformed in
today&rsquo;s machines&rdquo;&mdash;thus harboured the possibility of
becoming a kind of rehearsal of the revolution. &ldquo;[A]ll problems
of contemporary art&rdquo;, Benjamin insisted, &ldquo;find their
definitive formulation only in the context of film&rdquo; (AP, [K3,
3], 394). In this respect, it was the combination of the communist
pedagogy and constructive devices of Brecht&rsquo;s epic theatre that
marked it out for him as a theatre for the age of film (UB,
1&ndash;25; Wizisla 2009).</p>

<p>
Benjamin&rsquo;s writings on film are justly renowned for their twin
theses of the transformation of the concept of art by its
&lsquo;technical reproducibility&rsquo; and the new possibilities for
collective experience this contains, in the wake of the historical
decline of the &lsquo;aura&rsquo; of the work of art, a process that
film is presented as definitively concluding. Much ink has been spilt
debating the thesis of the decline of the aura in Benjamin&rsquo;s
work. On the one hand, with regard to some of his writings,
Benjamin&rsquo;s concept of aura has been accused of fostering a
nostalgic, purely negative sense of modernity as loss&mdash;loss of
unity both with nature and in community (A. Benjamin 1989). On the
other hand, in the work on film, Benjamin appears to adopt an
affirmative technological modernism, which celebrates the consequences
of the decline. Adorno, for one, felt betrayed by the latter position.
He wrote to Benjamin on 18 March 1936:</p>

<blockquote>
In your earlier writings&hellip; you distinguished the idea of the
work of art as a structure from the symbol of theology on the one
hand, and from the taboo of magic on the other. I now find it somewhat
disturbing &mdash;and here I can see a sublimated remnant of certain
Brechtian themes&mdash;that you have now rather casually transferred
the concept of the magical aura to the &lsquo;autonomous work of
work&rsquo; and flatly assigned a counter-revolutionary function to
the latter. (BA, 128)
</blockquote>

<p>
Brecht himself, meanwhile, was appalled by even the residually
negative function of the aura, recording his response in his
<em>Workbook</em>: &ldquo;it is all mysticism mysticism, in a posture
opposed to mysticism. &hellip; it is rather ghastly&rdquo; (cited in
Buck-Morss 1977, 149). Yet Adorno did not defend &lsquo;auratic
art&rsquo; as such. (His defence of autonomous art was grounded on the
experience derived from following the &lsquo;autonomous&rsquo;
technical development of laws of form.)</p>

<p>
Clearly, the concept of the aura plays a number of different roles in
Benjamin&rsquo;s writings, in his various attempts to grasp his
historical present in terms of the possibilities for
&lsquo;experience&rsquo; afforded by its new cultural forms; which he
increasingly came to identify (some say precipitously) with
revolutionary political potential. Yet Adorno was wrong to see a
simple change of position, rather than a complex series of inflections
of what was a generally consistent historical account. Benjamin had
written affirmatively of &ldquo;the emancipation of object from
aura&rdquo; as early as 1931, in his &lsquo;Little History of
Photography&rsquo;, in which he described Atget&rsquo;s photographs as
&ldquo;suck[ing] the aura out of reality like water from a sinking
ship&rdquo; (SW 2, 518). It is here that we find the basic definition
of aura: &ldquo;A strange weave of space and time: the unique
appearance or semblance of distance, no matter how close it may
be.&rdquo; Importantly, the examples given with this definition are
from nature: mountains and a branch observed &ldquo;at rest on a
summer&rsquo;s noon &hellip; until the moment or the hour become part
of their appearance&hellip;&rdquo;. The &lsquo;destruction&rsquo; of
the aura by transience and reproducibility is judged &ldquo;a salutary
estrangement&rdquo; (SW 2, 518&ndash;9). Similarly, when &lsquo;The
Storyteller&rsquo; recounts the &ldquo;dying out of the art of
storytelling&rdquo; and &ldquo;the incomparable aura that surrounds
the storyteller&rdquo;, it is nonetheless maintained: &ldquo;nothing
could be more fatuous than to wish to see it as merely a
&lsquo;symptom of decay&rsquo;, let alone a &lsquo;modern
symptom&rsquo;. It is rather, only a concomitant of the secular
productive forces of history&hellip;&rdquo; (SW 3, 146; 162).
&lsquo;The Work of Art&rsquo; essay extends and enriches the earlier
account of photography&rsquo;s technological transformation of
perception (&ldquo;the optical unconscious&rdquo;) with reference to
film. The difference resides in the insistent political dimension of
the later essay (after Hitler&rsquo;s taking of power in 1933), and
its determination to introduce concepts &ldquo;that are completely
useless for the purposes of fascism&rdquo; (SW 3, 102). The main
problem with the auratic (which is deemed historically residual, not
eliminated, indeed is perhaps ineliminable [Didi-Huberman 2004]) was
that, Benjamin believed, it was precisely &ldquo;useful for
fascism&rdquo;. This context over-determines the essay throughout,
with its almost Manichean oppositions between ritual and politics,
cult value and exhibition value. Quite apart from the intervening
technological and social developments, it makes it a very difficult
text simply to &lsquo;use&rsquo; today. For some, however, it is
precisely the connection it draws between a certain kind of mass
culture and fascism that provides its continuing relevance (Buck-Morss
1992).</p>

<h2><a id="BauMod">8. Baudelaire and the Modern</a></h2>

<p>
Benjamin&rsquo;s thinking of &lsquo;the modern&rsquo; [<em>die
Moderne</em>] is his most important theoretical contribution to the
historical study of cultural forms. Frequently mistranslated in early
English-language editions of his writings as &lsquo;modernism&rsquo;,
and still often rendered as &lsquo;modernity&rsquo; (although Benjamin
tended to retain Baudelaire&rsquo;s coinage, <em>la
modernit&eacute;</em>, when making that reference), <em>die
Moderne</em> designates both a formal temporal structure and the
diverse range of its historical instances&mdash;past and present.
Baudelaire is the main writer through whom Benjamin thought &lsquo;the
modern&rsquo;; not as might be expected, with reference to the
canonical account of <em>modernit&eacute;</em> in &lsquo;The Painter
of Modern Life&rsquo; (1859/60), but with regard to what Benjamin
called the &lsquo;theory&rsquo; of the modern first set down in
&lsquo;The Salon of 1845&rsquo;: &ldquo;the advent of the true <em>new
(die Heraufkunft des wahrhaft</em> Neunen)&rdquo; (SW 4, 45&ndash;6,
translation amended; GS 1.2, 580).</p>

<p>
In Baudelaire&rsquo;s &lsquo;The Painter&rsquo; essay,
<em>modernit&eacute;</em> famously denotes &lsquo;the ephemeral, the
fugitive, the contingent&rsquo;. It is associated with transitoriness
as the generalized social instantiation of the temporality of the
modern, in the capitalist metropolis. In contrast to transitoriness as
such, however, Benjamin was first and foremost (politically and
philosophically) interested in &lsquo;the new&rsquo;, in its
&lsquo;advent&rsquo; or historical becoming, and in its quality as
newness or novelty (the newness of the new), in a way that was
conceptually distinct from the conventional opposition of the
&lsquo;modern&rsquo; to the &lsquo;ancient&rsquo;&mdash;which
Baudelaire notoriously retained. As a result, Benjamin was
consequently also interested in what the German sociologist Max Weber
would have called its &lsquo;routinization&rsquo; (although Benjamin
did not use this vocabulary): the routinization accompanying the
generalization of the new as a mode of experience&mdash;in fashion and
boredom, in particular&mdash;and the formal structure of sameness
involved in its repetition. It is here that transitoriness enters the
picture&mdash;as a result of the generalization of novelty. Baudelaire
self-consciously embraced modernity with &lsquo;heroic effort&rsquo;,
attempting, like the painter of modern life, to &lsquo;extract its
epic aspects&rsquo; and &lsquo;distill the eternal from the
transitory&rsquo;; Benjamin, on the other hand, sought to understand
it in order to find a way out of what he called its
&lsquo;hell&rsquo;. He picked up on the relationship of the transitory
to the eternal in Baudelaire&rsquo;s account of modernity, but first,
he de-classicized the notion of the &lsquo;eternal&rsquo;, refiguring
it philosophically, and second, he rendered the relationship itself
strictly dialectical: in the modern, it is transitoriness itself that
is eternalized.</p>

<p>
Thus, Benjamin did not so much take over and update Baudelaire&rsquo;s
portrayal of modernity as read it &lsquo;symptomatically&rsquo; (in
Louis Althusser&rsquo;s sense), or more precisely, allegorically, in
order to uncover beneath it the experience of <em>the transformation
of historical time by the commodity form</em>. Baudelaire was able to
grasp this experience, according to Benjamin, through the
contradictory historical temporality that structured his work: at once
resolutely modern yet, in its poetic form (lyric), already
anachronistic. Benjamin similarly valued the disjunctive historical
temporality of Kafka&rsquo;s fables: their status as parables after
the &lsquo;end of storytelling&rsquo;. But whereas Kafka was for
Benjamin &ldquo;the figure of a failure&rdquo; (BS, 226)&mdash;the
inevitable failure of an attempt to translate the experience
[<em>Erlebnis</em>] of modernity into the language of tradition
(Judaism)&mdash;Baudelaire&rsquo;s poetry was able to convey the
intensity of the experience of modernity through the very tension
between that experience and his chosen, lyrical means; not merely
negatively (like Kafka), but via the way in which modernity
transformed those means. In particular, the lyric allowed Baudelaire
to register the full effect of the temporality of the modern on the
dissolution of subjectivity, and the fact that it consequently
&ldquo;takes a heroic constitution to live the modern [<em>die
Moderne</em>]&rdquo; (SW 4, 44, translation amended; GS 1.2, 577). The
extraction of the metropolitan &lsquo;motifs&rsquo; for which
Benjamin&rsquo;s reading of Baudelaire is justly famous&mdash;the
bohemian, the flaneur, the prostitute, the gambler, the
ragpicker&mdash;are the figures via which this structure of experience
appears. Primary within Baudelaire, they are nonetheless
methodologically secondary for Benjamin, as he explained to Adorno:
&ldquo;I only have to insert [them] in the appropriate place&rdquo;
(BA, 90). Baudelaire had found a method&mdash;what he called
&lsquo;correspondences&rsquo;&mdash;which reflectively incorporated
the anachronism of the lyric form into his work. Benjamin appropriated
this method, with its dissociated &lsquo;ritual elements&rsquo; (SW 4,
333), to read Baudelaire himself. In the essay &lsquo;Some Motifs in
Baudelaire&rsquo;, correspondences of temporal structure, experienced
as &lsquo;shock&rsquo;, link the machine, the film, the crowd, and the
game of chance:</p>

<blockquote>

<p>
What determines the rhythm of production on a conveyor belt is the
same thing that underlies the rhythm of reception in the film.
&hellip; The shock experience [<em>Chockerlebnis</em>] which the
passer-by has in the crowd corresponds to the isolated
&lsquo;experiences&rsquo; of the worker at his machine. &hellip; The
jolt in the movement of a machine is like the so-called coup in a game
of chance&hellip;. (SW 4, 328&ndash;30)</p>

<p>
A single repetitive and dissociated formal temporal structure is
detected beneath the rich array of phenomenological forms presented in
Baudelaire&rsquo;s poetry: &ldquo;the price for which the sensation of
the modern could be had: the disintegration of the aura in shock
experience&rdquo;. (SW 4, 343, translation amended; GS 1.2, 653)</p>
</blockquote>

<p>
Furthermore, this interpretative key, the experience of shock, is
itself understood through a series of theoretical correspondences
within Benjamin&rsquo;s own present; primarily, that between
Proust&rsquo;s &lsquo;involuntary memory&rsquo; and Freud&rsquo;s
theory of consciousness. This theoretical correspondence is read in
the light of the &lsquo;shell shock&rsquo; first diagnosed during the
First World War, about which Benjamin had previously written in his
reflections on Ernst Junger in his 1930 review essay, &lsquo;Theories
of German Fascism&rsquo; (SW 2, 312&ndash;321). The connection of the
modern to fascism does not appear solely through the thematic of the
false restoration of the aura, but also within the process of its
disintegration by shock. (Structurally, the shock of the crowd is
&lsquo;like&rsquo; shell shock.) Baudelaire is thus not merely the
privileged writer for the advent of the theory of the modern, but the
one in whose work the nineteenth century appears most clearly as the
fore-life of the present. However, if it was through Baudelaire that
Benjamin grasped the structure of the temporality of the
&lsquo;modern&rsquo;, it was through Nietzsche and Blanqui that he
explored its ambiguous historical meaning, via the way in which their
philosophies reflect the transformation of the new by the commodity
into the &lsquo;ever selfsame&rsquo;. &ldquo;Just as in the
seventeenth century it is allegory that becomes the canon of
dialectical images, in the nineteenth century it is novelty&rdquo;
(AP, 11): &ldquo;The commodity has taken the place of the allegorical
mode of apprehension.&rdquo; (SW 4, 188)</p>

<p>
It is the fragment &lsquo;Central Park&rsquo; that most clearly
reveals the consequences of Benjamin&rsquo;s reading of Baudelaire for
his concept of history: the modern completely transforms the
possibilities for the experience of history. On the one hand, it
de-historicizes experience, wresting it away from the temporal
continuities of tradition. On the other hand, a messianic
structure&mdash;an opening of history to something outside of
time&mdash;reasserts itself within the still life [<em>nature
mort</em>] of modernity&rsquo;s restless sameness. This is
Benjamin&rsquo;s famous &lsquo;dialectics at a standstill&rsquo;
(Tiedemann, 1982). It transforms the historical naturalism of the
baroque, analyzed in the <em>Origin of the German Mourning-Play</em>
(Section 4, above), in a futural direction. In particular, it involves
a prioritization of the interruptive stasis of the image over the
continuity of temporal succession. In fact, Benjamin maintained:
&ldquo;The concept of historical time forms an antithesis to the idea
of a temporal continuum&rdquo; (SW 4, 407).]</p>

<h2><a id="ImaHisCul">9. Image, History, Culture</a></h2>

<p>
Debate over Benjamin&rsquo;s conception of history was for many years
preoccupied with the question of whether it is essentially
&lsquo;theological&rsquo; or &lsquo;materialist&rsquo; in character
(or how it could possibly be both at once), occasioned by the
conjunction of Benjamin&rsquo;s self-identification with historical
materialism and his continued use of explicitly messianic motifs
(Wolhfarth 1978; Tiedemann 1983&ndash;4). This was in large part the
polemical legacy of the competing influence of three
friendships&mdash;with Gershom Scholem, Theodor W. Adorno and Bertolt
Brecht&mdash;applied to the interpretation of Benjamin&rsquo;s final
text, the fragments &lsquo;On the Concept of History&rsquo;
(&lsquo;<em>&Uuml;ber den Begriff der Geschichte</em>&rsquo;,
popularly known as the &lsquo;Theses on the Philosophy of
History&rsquo;). Scholem promoted a theological interpretation, Brecht
inspired a materialist one, while Adorno attempted to forge some form
of compatibility between the two. Yet the question is badly posed if
it is framed within received concepts of &lsquo;theology&rsquo; and
&lsquo;materialism&rsquo; (the paradox becomes self-sustaining), since
it was Benjamin&rsquo;s aim radically to rethink the meaning of these
ideas, on the basis of a new philosophy of historical time. This new
philosophy of historical time is the ultimate goal of Benjamin&rsquo;s
later writings. It appears most explicitly, under construction, in
&lsquo;Convolute N&rsquo; of <em>The Arcades Project</em>, &lsquo;On
the Theory of Knowledge, Theory of Progress&rsquo;; it is applied to
art history in the 1937 essay &lsquo;Eduard Fuch, Collector and
Historian&rsquo;; and is manifest in a condensed, rhetorically
political and problematic form in &lsquo;On the Concept of
History&rsquo;. It derives from a dual critique of the &lsquo;vulgar
naturalism&rsquo; of <em>historicism</em> and the deferral of action
involved in the associated Social Democratic concept of
<em>progress</em> (Kittsteiner 1986). It gives rise to a conception of
historical intelligibility based on &lsquo;literary montage&rsquo; as
the method of construction of &lsquo;dialectical images&rsquo; (AP,
460&ndash;1). And it culminates in a quasi-messianic conception of
revolution as an &lsquo;interruption&rsquo; of history or an
&lsquo;arrest of happening&rsquo;: &ldquo;Classless society is not the
final goal of historical progress but its frequently miscarried,
ultimately achieved interruption&rdquo; (SW 4, 402).</p>

<p>
Benjamin took as one of the main &lsquo;methodological
objectives&rsquo; of his <em>Arcades Project</em> &ldquo;to
demonstrate a historical materialism which has annihilated within
itself the idea of progress&rdquo;, taking as its &ldquo;founding
concept&hellip; not progress but actualization&rdquo; (AP, [N2, 2],
460). He had both philosophical and political reasons for this.
Philosophically, Benjamin saw the conventional idea of progress as
projecting into the future a conception of time as
&lsquo;homogenous&rsquo; and &lsquo;empty&rsquo; epitomized by the
attempt of Ranke&rsquo;s historicism to represent the past &ldquo;the
way it really was&rdquo; (SW4, 395; 391). This is a conception of time
based on the temporal continuity of past, present and future,
&lsquo;in&rsquo; which events occur and are understood as causally
connected. It is naturalistic in so far as it acknowledges no
fundamental temporal-ontological distinction between past, present and
future time; it has no sense of time as the ongoing production of
temporal differentiation. Time is differentiated solely by the
differences between the events that occur within it. In particular, it
fails to grasp that historical time (the time of human life) is
constituted through such immanent differentiations, via the
existential modes of memory, expectation and action. In this respect,
there are affinities between Benjamin&rsquo;s philosophy of time and
Heidegger&rsquo;s (Caygill, 1994).</p>

<p>
The political consequence of the temporal naturalism underlying the
idea of &lsquo;progress&rsquo; is conformism. For Benjamin,
paradoxically, this applied in particular to the German Social
Democrats&rsquo; understanding of communism as an <em>ideal</em>, in
the neo-Kantian ethical sense of the object of an &lsquo;endless
task&rsquo;:</p>

<blockquote>
Once the classless society had been defined as an infinite task, the
empty homogeneous time was transformed into an anteroom, so to speak,
in which one could wait for the emergence of the revolutionary
situation with more or less equanimity. (SW 4, 402)
</blockquote>

<p>
In other words, the concept of progress is demobilizing; and Marxism
had become infected by the ideology of progress. However, rather than
positing an existential alternative, in the manner of
Heidegger&rsquo;s &lsquo;resolute decision&rsquo;, Benjamin set out to
construct novel conceptions of historical time and historical
intelligibility based on the relationship, not between the past and
the present, but between the &lsquo;then&rsquo; and the
&lsquo;now&rsquo;, as brought together in images of the past. Each
historically specific &lsquo;now&rsquo; was understood to correspond
to (in a Baudelairean sense), or to render legible, a particular
&lsquo;then&rsquo;.</p>

<blockquote>
It is not that what is past casts its light on what is present, or
what is present its light on what is past; rather, an image is that
wherein what has been comes together in a flash with the now to form a
constellation. In other words: image is dialectics at a standstill.
For while the relation of the present to the past is purely temporal,
the relation of what-has-been to the now is dialectical: not temporal
in nature but figural [<em>bildlich</em>]. Only dialectical images are
genuinely historical &hellip; (AP, [N3, 1], 463)
</blockquote>

<p>
The experimental method of montage, borrowed from surrealism, was to
be the means of production of historical intelligibility. Furthermore,
the &lsquo;static&rsquo; temporality of the image was understood to
connect such an experience of historical meaning, directly, to a
radical or &lsquo;revolutionary&rsquo; concept of action, associated
with the idea of the present as crisis. The passage above
continues:</p>

<blockquote>
The image that is read&mdash;which is to say, the image in the now of
its recognizability [<em>das Bild im Jetzt der
Erkennbarkeik</em>]&mdash;bears to the highest degree the imprint of
the perilous critical moment on which all reading is founded. (AP,
[N3, 1], 463)
</blockquote>

<p>
Such &ldquo;perilous critical moments&rdquo; are both immanent to the
temporality of modernity, at a structural level (the temporality of
crisis), and, in each particular case, contingent and conjuncturally
specific. In them, the past is understood &ldquo;to bring the present
into a critical state&rdquo;. However, this critical state is not a
crisis of the status quo, but rather of its destruction: the critical
moment is that in which &ldquo;the status quo threatens to be
preserved&rdquo; (AP, [N10, 2], 474). Dialectical images counter the
threat of preservation (tradition) by virtue of the interruptive force
they are understood to impart to experience as a consequence of the
instantaneous temporality of the now, or what Benjamin famously called
now-time [<em>Jetztzeit</em>]: &ldquo;The dialectical image is an
image that emerges suddenly, in a flash&rdquo; (AP, [N9, 7], 473). It
is this image of the image as a &lsquo;flash&rsquo; [<em>ein
aufblitzendes</em>] and the corresponding image of historical
experience as the discharge of an explosive force&mdash;the explosive
force of now-time, blasting open &lsquo;the continuum of
history&rsquo;&mdash;for which Benjamin is probably best known. The
philosophy of historical time which these images sum up was elaborated
by him in two main contexts: the development of a new conception of
cultural history and a political diagnosis of the historical crisis of
Europe at the outset of the Second World War.</p>

<p>
Benjamin did not see culture as threatened by &lsquo;barbarism&rsquo;,
so much as itself being implicated in it:</p>

<blockquote>
Barbarism lurks in the very concept of culture&mdash;as the concept of
a fund of values which is considered independent not, indeed, of the
production process in which these values originated, but of the one in
which they survive. In this way they serve the apotheosis of the
latter, barbaric as it may be. (AP, [N5a, 7] 467&ndash;8)
</blockquote>

<p>
The concept of culture as the values of a heritage was for Benjamin
&lsquo;fetishistic&rsquo;: &ldquo;Culture appears reified.&rdquo; Only
an understanding of &ldquo;the crucial importance of reception&hellip;
enables us to correct the process of reification which takes place in
a work of art&rdquo; (SW 3, 267; 269). For Benjamin, however,
reception&mdash;or what he called the &lsquo;afterlife&rsquo;
[<em>Nachleben</em>] of the work&mdash;was not merely something that
happened to the work, externally; it was as <em>constitutive</em> of
the work itself as its &lsquo;fore-life&rsquo; [<em>Vorleben</em>], or
conditions of production&mdash;which are themselves rendered invisible
by the idea of culture as value, and are themselves &ldquo;involved in
a constant process of change&rdquo; as the work itself changes. A
materialist cultural history would restore to the experience of works
a sense of both of these changing sets of conditions (before and
after), and the conflicts between them, in an engagement
&ldquo;originary for every present&rdquo;, since &ldquo;[i]t is the
present that polarizes the event into fore- and after-history&rdquo;
(SW 3, 261&ndash;2; AP, [N7a, 8], 471). It is here, in an ontological
rethinking of reception, that the philosophical significance of
Benjamin&rsquo;s interest in technologies of reproduction lies. With
these concepts of fore- and afterlife, Benjamin founded a new
problematic for cultural study.</p>

<p>
Benjamin was interested in &lsquo;culture&rsquo; not as an autonomous
realm of values (&ldquo;the independent values of aesthetic,
scientific, ethical&hellip; and even religious achievements&rdquo;),
but on the contrary, like the sociologist Georg Simmel, whose
<em>Philosophy of Money</em> he cities in this regard, as
&ldquo;elements in the development of human nature&rdquo; (Simmel,
quoted in AP, [N14, 3], 480). In this respect, cultural study is
situated within the field of a materialist philosophy of history. And
the philosophy of history insists on a conception of history as a
whole. It is here than the messianic structure of Benajmin&rsquo;s
concept of history confronts us as unavoidable; although not thereby
necessarily &lsquo;theological&rsquo;, since it is the transition of a
conceptual structure from one philosophical context into another that
is at issue (Benjamin&rsquo;s favorite surrealist method of
&lsquo;decontextualization&rsquo; and
&lsquo;defamiliarization&rsquo;), not its meaning in its original
theological context as such. In his search for a non-Hegelian,
non-developmentalist conception of history as a whole, in &lsquo;On
the Concept of History&rsquo; Benjamin figured now-time,
quasi-messianically, alternatively as a &lsquo;model&rsquo; of
messianic time and as &ldquo;shot through with splinters of messianic
time.&rdquo; In the context of a diagnosis of the European crisis of
1939&ndash;40 as a world-historical crisis, the &lsquo;critical state
of the present&rsquo; thus came, in this text, to acquire a
theological-political tenor. &ldquo;A revolutionary chance in the
fight for the oppressed past&rdquo; is compared to &ldquo;the sign of
a messianic arrest of happening&rdquo; (SW 4, 396&ndash;7). Benjamin
was aware that this rhetoric would lead to misunderstanding. But the
combination of perceived political urgency and isolation compelled him
to extend his concept of history beyond the state of his philosophical
research, experimentally, into an apparently definitive statement. It
is as if Benjamin had hoped to overcome the aporia of action within
his still essentially hermeneutical philosophy (Osborne 1995) through
the force of language alone. Formally, however, &lsquo;On the Concept
of History&rsquo; should be read as a series of fragments, in the
early Romantic sense. As such, it remains resolutely
negative&mdash;and thereby importantly partial&mdash;in its evocation
of the historical whole, which is acknowledged as unpresentable. In
this respect, Benjamin&rsquo;s final text recalls his earliest major
publication, the 1919 thesis &lsquo;The Concept of Art Criticism in
German Romanticism&rsquo;: as a gesture towards the philosophy of
history needed to complete a modified and &lsquo;modernized&rsquo;
version of the early Romantic project.</p>
</div>

